# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cinnaholic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta was originally founded as the terminus of a major state-sponsored railroad, but soon became the convergence point for several railroad lines, spurring its rapid growth.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The largest of these was the Western and Atlantic Railroad, from which the name "Atlanta" is derived, reflecting the city's growing reputation as a major transportation hub.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] During the American Civil War, the city served a strategically important role for the Confederacy.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] It was captured in 1864 following the Atlanta campaign, and under Union General William T.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Sherman, Atlanta was almost entirely burned to the ground during the March to the Sea.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta rebounded dramatically in the post–Civil War period and quickly became a national industrial center and the unofficial capital of the "New South".
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] After World War II, Atlanta emerged as a manufacturing and technology hub.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] During the 1950s and 1960s, it became a major organizing center of the American civil rights movement, with Martin Luther King Jr., Ralph Abernathy, and many other locals serving as prominent leaders.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In the modern era, Atlanta has remained a major transportation center, with Hartsfield-Jackson International Airport becoming the world's busiest airport by passenger traffic in 1998.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] It has maintained this position every year since, except in 2020, with an estimated 93.7 million passengers in 2022.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] With a nominal gross domestic product (GDP) of $473 billion in 2021, Atlanta has the 11th-largest economy among U.S. cities and the 22nd-largest in the world.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Its economy is diverse, with dominant sectors including transportation, aerospace, logistics, healthcare, news and media operations, film and television production, information technology, finance, biomedical research, and public policy.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta established itself on the world stage when it won the bid to host the 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The Games had a lasting impact on Atlanta's development into the 21st century, leading to significant investment in the city's universities, parks, and tourism industry.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The gentrification of some of its neighborhoods has intensified in the 21st century with the growth of the Atlanta Beltline rail trail, altering Atlanta's demographics, politics, aesthetics, and culture.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] For thousands of years prior to the arrival of European settlers in North Georgia, the indigenous Creek people, Cherokee people, and their ancestors inhabited the area.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Standing Peachtree, a Creek village where Peachtree Creek flows into the Chattahoochee River, was the closest Native American settlement to what is now Atlanta.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Through the early 19th century, European Americans systematically encroached on the Creek of northern Georgia, forcing them out of the area from 1802 to 1825.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The Creek were forced to leave the area in 1821, under Indian Removal by the federal government, and European American settlers arrived the following year.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In 1836, the Georgia General Assembly voted to build the Western and Atlantic Railroad in order to provide a link between the port of Savannah and the Midwest.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The initial route was to run southward from Chattanooga to a terminus east of the Chattahoochee River, which would be linked to Savannah.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] After engineers surveyed various possible locations for the terminus, the "zero milepost" was driven into the ground in what is now Foundry Street, Five Points.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] When asked in 1837 about the future of the little village, Stephen Harriman Long, the railroad's chief engineer said the place would be good "for one tavern, a blacksmith shop, a grocery store, and nothing else".
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] A year later, the area around the milepost had developed into a settlement, first known as *Terminus*, and later *Thrasherville*, after a local merchant who built homes and a general store in the area.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] By 1842, the town had six buildings and 30 residents and was renamed *Marthasville* to honor Governor Wilson Lumpkin's daughter Martha.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Later, John Edgar Thomson, Chief Engineer of the Georgia Railroad, suggested the town be renamed *Atlanta*, supposedly a feminine version of the word "Atlantic", referring to the Western and Atlantic Railroad.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] (Atalanta was also Martha Lumpkin's middle name.) The residents approved, and the town was incorporated as Atlanta on December 29, 1847.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] By 1860, Atlanta's population had grown to 9,554.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] During the American Civil War, the nexus of multiple railroads in Atlanta made the city a strategic hub for the distribution of military supplies.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In 1864, the Union Army moved southward following the capture of Chattanooga and began its invasion of north Georgia.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The region surrounding Atlanta was the location of several major army battles, culminating with the Battle of Atlanta and a four-month-long siege of the city by the Union Army under the command of General William Tecumseh Sherman.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] On September 1, 1864, Confederate General John Bell Hood decided to retreat from Atlanta, and he ordered the destruction of all public buildings and possible assets that could be of use to the Union Army.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] On the next day, Mayor James Calhoun surrendered Atlanta to the Union Army, and on September 7, Sherman ordered the city's civilian population to evacuate.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] On November 11, 1864, Sherman prepared for the Union Army's March to the Sea by ordering the destruction of Atlanta's remaining military assets.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] After the Civil War ended in 1865, Atlanta was gradually rebuilt during the Reconstruction era.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Due to the city's superior rail transportation network, the state capital was moved from Milledgeville to Atlanta in 1868.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In the 1880 Census, Atlanta had surpassed Savannah as Georgia's largest city.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Grady, the editor of the *Atlanta Constitution* newspaper, promoted Atlanta to potential investors as a city of the "New South" that would be based upon a modern economy and less reliant on agriculture.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] By 1885, the founding of the Georgia School of Technology (now the Georgia Institute of Technology) and the Atlanta University Center, a consortium of historically black colleges made up of units for men and women, had established Atlanta as a center for higher education.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In 1895, Atlanta hosted the Cotton States and International Exposition, which attracted nearly 800,000 attendees and successfully promoted the New South's development to the world.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] During the first decades of the 20th century, Atlanta enjoyed a period of unprecedented growth.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In three decades' time, Atlanta's population tripled as the city limits expanded to include nearby streetcar suburbs.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The city's skyline grew taller with the construction of the Equitable, Flatiron, Empire, and Candler buildings.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Sweet Auburn emerged as a center of Black commerce.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The period was also marked by strife and tragedy.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Increased racial tensions led to the Atlanta Race Riot of 1906, when Whites attacked Blacks, leaving at least 27 people dead and over 70 injured, with extensive damage in Black neighborhoods.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In 1913, Leo Frank, a Jewish-American factory superintendent, was convicted of the murder of a 13-year-old girl in a highly publicized trial.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] He was sentenced to death, but the governor commuted his sentence to life.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] An enraged and organized lynch mob took him from jail in 1915 and hanged him in Marietta.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The Jewish community in Atlanta and across the country were horrified.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] On May 21, 1917, the Great Atlanta Fire destroyed 1,938 buildings in what is now the Old Fourth Ward, resulting in one fatality and the displacement of 10,000 people.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] On December 15, 1939, Atlanta hosted the premiere of *Gone with the Wind*, the epic film based on the best-selling novel by Atlanta's Margaret Mitchell.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The gala event at Loew's Grand Theatre was attended by the film's legendary producer, David O.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Selznick, and the film's stars Clark Gable, Vivien Leigh, and Olivia de Havilland, but Oscar winner Hattie McDaniel, an African-American actress, was barred from the event due to racial segregation laws.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta played a vital role in the Allied effort during World War II.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Colonel Blake Van Leer, the president of Georgia Tech, played a significant part by lobbying war-related manufacturing companies like Lockheed Martin to move to Atlanta, successfully lobbying the Government to build military bases, in turn helping attract thousands of new residents through new jobs.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Van Leer also launched major research centers, which included Neely Nuclear Research Center and funds to help make Georgia Tech the "MIT" of the south while also founding Southern Polytechnic State University.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] These new defense industries attracted thousands of new residents and generated revenues, resulting in rapid population and economic growth.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In the 1950s, the city's newly constructed highway system, supported by federal subsidies, allowed middle-class Atlantans the ability to relocate to the suburbs.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] As a result, the city began to make up an ever-smaller proportion of the metropolitan area's population.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] African-American veterans returned from World War II seeking full rights in their country and began heightened activism.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In exchange for support by that portion of the Black community that could vote, in 1948 the mayor ordered the hiring of the first eight African-American police officers in the city.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Much controversy preceded the 1956 Sugar Bowl, when the Pitt Panthers, with African-American fullback Bobby Grier on the roster, met the Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] There had been controversy over whether Grier should be allowed to play due to his race, and whether Georgia Tech should even play at all due to Georgia's Governor Marvin Griffin's opposition to racial integration.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] After Griffin publicly sent a telegram to the state's Board of Regents requesting Georgia Tech not to engage in racially integrated events, Georgia Tech's president Blake R.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Van Leer rejected the request and threatened to resign.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Later, students from both Georgia Tech and the University of Georgia held a protest against Griffin's stance, which soon turned into a riot.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The students broke windows, upturned parking meters, hung Griffin in effigy, and marched all the way to the governor's mansion, surrounding it until 3:30 a.m.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Griffin publicly blamed Georgia Tech's president for the "riots" and requested he be replaced and Georgia Tech's state funding be cut off.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] On December 5 the Georgia Tech board of regents voted 13–1 in favor of allowing the game to proceed as scheduled.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In the 1960s, Atlanta became a major organizing center of the civil rights movement, with Martin Luther King Jr., Ralph Abernathy, and students from Atlanta's historically black colleges and universities playing major roles in the movement's leadership.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] While Atlanta in the postwar years had relatively minimal racial strife compared to other cities, Blacks were limited by discrimination, segregation, and continued disenfranchisement of most voters.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Desegregation of the public sphere came in stages, with public transportation desegregated by 1959, the restaurant at Rich's department store by 1961, movie theaters by 1963, and public schools by 1973 (nearly 20 years after the U.S.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Supreme Court ruled that segregated public schools were unconstitutional).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In 1960, Whites comprised 61.7% of the city's population.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] During the 1950s–70s, suburbanization and White flight from urban areas led to a significant demographic shift.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] By 1970, African Americans were the majority of the city's population and exercised their recently enforced voting rights and political influence by electing Atlanta's first Black mayor, Maynard Jackson, in 1973.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Under Mayor Jackson's tenure, Atlanta's airport was modernized, strengthening the city's role as a transportation center.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The opening of the Georgia World Congress Center in 1976 further confirmed Atlanta's rise as a convention city.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Construction of the city's subway system began in 1975, with rail service commencing in 1979.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Despite these improvements, Atlanta lost more than 100,000 residents between 1970 and 1990, over 20% of its population.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] At the same time, it developed new office space after attracting numerous corporations, with an increasing portion of workers from northern areas.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta was selected as the site for the 1996 Summer Olympic Games.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Following the announcement, the city government undertook several major construction projects to improve Atlanta's parks, sporting venues, and transportation infrastructure; however, for the first time, none of the $1.7 billion cost of the games was governmentally funded.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] While the games experienced transportation and accommodation problems and the Centennial Olympic Park bombing occurred despite extra security precautions, the spectacle was still a watershed event in Atlanta's history.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] According to former Mayor Kasim Reed, the Olympic Games generated "a direct economic impact of at least USD 5 billion".
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] For the first time in Olympic history, every one of the record 197 national Olympic committees invited to compete sent athletes, sending more than 10,000 contestants participating in a record 271 events.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The related projects, such as Atlanta's Olympic Legacy Program and civic efforts, initiated a fundamental transformation of the city in the following decade.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] During the 2000s, the city of Atlanta underwent a profound physical, cultural, and demographic change.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] As some of the African-American middle and upper classes also began to move to the suburbs, a booming economy drew numerous new migrants from other cities in the United States, who contributed to changes in the city's demographics.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] African Americans made up a decreasing portion of the population, from a high of 67% in 1990 to 54% in 2010.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] From 2000 to 2010, Atlanta gained 22,763 white residents, 5,142 Asian residents, and 3,095 Hispanic residents, while the city's Black population decreased by 31,678.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Much of the city's demographic change during the decade was driven by young, college-educated professionals: from 2000 to 2009, the three-mile radius surrounding Downtown Atlanta gained 9,722 residents aged 25 to 34 and holding at least a four-year degree, an increase of 61%.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] This was similar to the tendency in other cities for young, college educated, single or married couples to live in downtown areas.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In the lead-up to the 1996 Summer Olympics, the Atlanta Housing Authority demolished nearly all of its public housing.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Residents instead received vouchers to pay for private housing; a wave of mixed housing was built using funding from the HOPE VI program under CEO Renee Lewis Glover (1994–2013).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In 2005, the city approved the $2.8 billion Beltline project.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] It was intended to convert a disused 22-mile freight railroad loop that surrounds the central city into an art-filled multi-use trail and light rail transit line, which would increase the city's park space by 40%.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The project stimulated retail and residential development along the loop, but has been criticized for its adverse effects on some Black communities.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In 2013, the project received a federal grant of $18 million to develop the southwest corridor.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Cox Foundation gave $6 million to the PATH Foundation which will connect the Silver Comet Trail to The Atlanta Beltline, which was expected to be completed by 2022.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Upon completion, the total combined interconnected trail distance around Atlanta for the Atlanta Beltline and Silver Comet Trail will be the longest paved trail surface in the U.S., totaling about 300 miles (480 km).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta's cultural offerings expanded during the 2000s: the High Museum of Art doubled in size; the Alliance Theatre won a Tony Award; and art galleries were established on the once-industrial Westside.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The College Football Hall of Fame relocated to Atlanta and the National Center for Civil and Human Rights museum was constructed.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The city of Atlanta was the subject of a massive cyberattack which began in March 2018.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In December 2019, Atlanta hosted the Miss Universe 2019 pageant competition.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] On June 16, 2022, Atlanta was selected as a host city for the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta encompasses 134.0 square miles (347.1 km2), of which 133.2 square miles (344.9 km2) is land and 0.85 square miles (2.2 km2) is water.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The city is situated in the Deep South of the southeastern United States among the foothills of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] At 1,050 feet (320 m) above mean sea level, Atlanta has the highest elevation among major cities east of the Mississippi River.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta straddles the Eastern Continental Divide.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Rainwater that falls on the south and east side of the divide flows into the Atlantic Ocean, while rainwater on the north and west side of the divide flows into the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta developed on a ridge south of the Chattahoochee River, which is part of the ACF River Basin.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The river borders the far northwestern edge of the city, and much of its natural habitat has been preserved, in part by the Chattahoochee River National Recreation Area.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta is 21 miles (34 km) southeast of Marietta, 27 miles (43 km) southwest of Alpharetta, 146 miles (235 km) southwest of Greenville, South Carolina, 147 miles (237 km) east of Birmingham, Alabama, and 245 miles (394 km) southwest of Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Despite having lost significant tree canopy coverage between 1973 and 1999, Atlanta now has the densest urban tree coverage of any major city in the United States and is often called "City of Trees" or "The City in a Forest".
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta is divided into 242 officially defined neighborhoods.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The city contains three major high-rise districts, which form a north–south axis along Peachtree: Downtown, Midtown, and Buckhead.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Surrounding these high-density districts are leafy, low-density neighborhoods, most of which are dominated by single-family homes.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Downtown contains the most office space in the metro area, much of it occupied by government entities.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Downtown is home to the city's sporting venues and many of its tourist attractions.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Midtown is the city's second-largest business district, containing the offices of many of the region's law firms.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Midtown is known for its art institutions, cultural attractions, institutions of higher education, and dense form.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Buckhead, the city's uptown district, is eight miles (13 km) north of Downtown and the city's third-largest business district.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The district is marked by an urbanized core along Peachtree Road, surrounded by suburban single-family neighborhoods situated among woods and rolling hills.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Surrounding Atlanta's three high-rise districts are the city's low- and medium-density neighborhoods, where the craftsman bungalow single-family home is dominant.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The eastside is marked by historic streetcar suburbs, built from the 1890s to the 1930s as havens for the upper middle class.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] These neighborhoods, many of which contain their own villages encircled by shaded, architecturally distinct residential streets, include the Victorian Inman Park, Bohemian East Atlanta, and eclectic Old Fourth Ward.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In southwest Atlanta, neighborhoods closer to downtown originated as streetcar suburbs, including the historic West End, while those farther from downtown retain a postwar suburban layout.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] These include Collier Heights and Cascade Heights, historically home to most of the city's upper middle-class African-American population.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Northwest Atlanta contains the areas of the city to west of Marietta Boulevard and to the north of Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Drive, including those neighborhoods remote to downtown, such as Riverside, Bolton and Whittier Mill.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The latter is one of Atlanta's designated Landmark Historical Neighborhoods.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Vine City, though technically Northwest, adjoins the city's Downtown area and has recently been the target of community outreach programs and economic development initiatives.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Gentrification of the city's neighborhoods is one of the more controversial and transformative forces shaping contemporary Atlanta.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The gentrification of Atlanta has its origins in the 1970s, after many of Atlanta's neighborhoods had declined and suffered the urban decay that affected other major American cities in the mid-20th century.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] When neighborhood opposition successfully prevented two freeways from being built through the city's east side in 1975, the area became the starting point for Atlanta's gentrification.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] After Atlanta was awarded the Olympic Games in 1990, gentrification expanded into other parts of the city, stimulated by infrastructure improvements undertaken in preparation for the games.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] New development post-2000 has been aided by the Atlanta Housing Authority's eradication of the city's public housing.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] As noted above, it allowed the development of these sites for mixed-income housing, requiring developers to reserve a considerable portion for affordable housing units.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] It has also provided for other former residents to be given vouchers to gain housing in other areas.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Construction of the Beltline has stimulated new and related development along its path.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Most of Atlanta was burned in the final months of the American Civil War, depleting the city of a large stock of its historic architecture.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Yet architecturally, the city had never been traditionally "southern": Atlanta originated as a railroad town rather than a southern seaport dominated by the planter class, such as Savannah or Charleston.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Because of its later development, many of the city's landmarks share architectural characteristics with buildings in the Northeast or Midwest, as they were designed at a time of shared national architectural styles.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] During the late 20th century, Atlanta embraced the global trend of modern architecture, especially for commercial and institutional structures.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Examples include the State of Georgia Building, built in 1966, and the Georgia-Pacific Tower in 1982.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Many of the most notable examples from this period were designed by world-renowned Atlanta architect John Portman.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Most of the buildings that define the downtown skyline were designed by Portman during this period, including the Westin Peachtree Plaza and the Atlanta Marriott Marquis.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In the latter half of the 1980s, Atlanta became one of the early homes of postmodern buildings that reintroduced classical elements to their designs.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Many of Atlanta's tallest skyscrapers were built in this period and style, displaying tapering spires or otherwise ornamented crowns, such as One Atlantic Center (1987), 191 Peachtree Tower (1991), and the Four Seasons Hotel Atlanta (1992).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Also completed during the era was the Bank of America Plaza, built in 1992.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] At 1,023 feet (312 m), it is the tallest building in the city and the 14th-tallest in the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The city's embrace of modern architecture has often translated into an ambivalent approach toward historic preservation, leading to the destruction of many notable architectural landmarks.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In the mid-1970s, the Fox Theatre, now a cultural icon of the city, would have met the same fate if not for a grassroots effort to save it.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] More recently, preservationists may have made some inroads.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] For example, in 2016 activists convinced the Atlanta City Council not to demolish the Atlanta-Fulton Central Library, the last building designed by noted architect Marcel Breuer.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Under the Köppen classification, Atlanta has a humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*) with generous precipitation year-round, typical for the Upland South.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The city is situated in USDA Plant Hardiness Zone 8a, with the northern and western suburbs, as well as part of Midtown transitioning to 7b.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Summers are hot and humid, with temperatures somewhat moderated by the city's elevation.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Winters are overall mild but variable, occasionally susceptible to snowstorms even if in small quantities on several occasions, unlike the central and southern portions of the state.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Warm air from the Gulf of Mexico can bring spring-like highs while strong Arctic air masses can push lows into the teens °F (−7 to −12 °C).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] July averages 80.9 °F (27.2 °C), with high temperatures reaching 90 °F (32 °C) on an average of 47 days per year, though 100 °F (38 °C) readings are not seen most years.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] January averages 44.8 °F (7.1 °C), with temperatures in the suburbs slightly cooler due largely to the urban heat island effect.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Lows at or below freezing can be expected 36 nights annually, but the last occurrences of temperatures below 10 °F (−12 °C) were December 24, 2022, and January 2014, eight years apart.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Average dewpoints in the summer range from 63.7 °F (17.6 °C) in June to 67.8 °F (19.9 °C) in July.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Typical of the southeastern U.S., Atlanta receives abundant rainfall that is evenly distributed throughout the year, though late spring and early fall are somewhat drier.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The average annual precipitation is 50.43 in (1,281 mm), while snowfall is typically light and rare, with a normal of 2.2 inches (5.6 cm) per winter.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The heaviest single snowfall occurred on January 23, 1940, with around 10 inches (25 cm) of snow.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] However, ice storms usually cause more problems than snowfall does, the most severe occurring on January 7, 1973.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Tornadoes are rare in the city itself, but the March 14, 2008, EF2 tornado damaged prominent structures in downtown Atlanta.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The 2020 United States census reported that Atlanta had a population of 498,715.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The population density was 3,685.45 persons per square mile (1,422.95/km2).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The racial and ethnic makeup of Atlanta (including Hispanics) was 51.0% Black or African American, 40.9% non-Hispanic white, 4.2% Asian, and 0.3% Native American, and 1.0% from other races.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] 2.4% of the population reported two or more races.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Hispanics and Latinos of any race made up 6.0% of the city's population.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The median income for a household in the city was $77,655 in 2022.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The per capita income for the city was $60,778 in 2022.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Approximately 17.7% percent of the population was living below the poverty line in 2022.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Circa 2024, of the Atlanta residents, 391,711 of them lived in Fulton County and 28,292 of them lived in DeKalb County.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In the 1920s, the Black population began to grow in Southern metropolitan cities like Atlanta, Birmingham, Houston, and Memphis.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Since the 1970s, Atlanta has been widely recognized as a hub of African American political activism, education, entrepreneurship, and culture—earning it the reputation of being a Black mecca.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] However, in the 1990s, Atlanta started to experience Black flight.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] African Americans have moved outside the city seeking a lower cost of living or better public schools.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The African American share of Atlanta's population has declined faster than any other racial group.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The city's share of Black residents shrank from 67% in 1990 to 47% in 2020.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Blacks made up nine percent of new Atlanta residents between 2010 and 2020.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] At the same time, Atlanta is home to a sizable foreign-born Black population, notably from Eritrea, Ethiopia, Ghana, Somalia, Liberia, and Nigeria.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] With many notable investments occurring in Atlanta initiated by the 1996 Summer Olympics, the non-Hispanic White population of Atlanta began to rebound after several decades of White flight to Atlanta's suburbs.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Between 2000 and 2020, the proportion of Whites in the city had strong growth.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In two decades, Atlanta's White population grew from 33% to 39% of the city's population.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Whites made up the majority of new Atlanta residents between 2010 and 2020.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The Hispanic and Latino populations in Metro Atlanta have experienced significant growth.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The largest Hispanic ancestries in Atlanta are Mexican, Puerto Rican and Cuban.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] There is a growing population of Mexican ancestry throughout the region, with notable concentrations along the Buford Highway and I-85 corridor, and now extending into Gwinnett County.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In 2013, Metro Atlanta had the 19th largest Hispanic population in the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The Atlanta area also has a fast growing Asian American population.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The largest groups of Asian origin are those of Indian, Vietnamese, Chinese, Korean, Filipino, Pakistani and Japanese descent.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Pew Research Center ranks the Atlanta area among the top 10 U.S. metropolitan areas by Indian population in 2019.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Early immigrants in the Atlanta area were mostly Jews and Greeks.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Since 2010, the Atlanta area has experienced notable immigration from India, China, South Korea, and Jamaica.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Other notable source countries of immigrants are Vietnam, Eritrea, Nigeria, the Arabian gulf, Ukraine and Poland.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Within a few decades, and in keeping with national trends, immigrants from England, Ireland, and German-speaking central Europe were no longer the majority of Atlanta's foreign-born population.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The city's Italians included immigrants from northern Italy, many of whom had been in Atlanta since the 1890s; more recent arrivals from southern Italy; and Sephardic Jews from the Isle of Rhodes, which Italy had seized from Turkey in 1912.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Europeans from Great Britain, Ireland and Germany settled in the city as early as the 1840s.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Most of Atlanta's European population is from the United Kingdom and Germany.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Vietnamese people, Cambodians, Ethiopians, and Eritreans were the earliest refugees formally brought to the city.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Of the total population five years and older, 83.3% spoke only English at home, while 8.8% spoke Spanish, 3.9% another Indo-European language, and 2.8% an Asian language.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Among them, 7.3% of Atlantans were born abroad (86th in the U.S.).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta's dialect has traditionally been a variation of Southern American English.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The Chattahoochee River long formed a border between the Coastal Southern and Southern Appalachian dialects.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Because of the development of corporate headquarters in the region, attracting migrants from other areas of the country, by 2003, *Atlanta* magazine concluded that Atlanta had become significantly "de-Southernized".
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] A Southern accent was considered a handicap in some circumstances.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In general, Southern accents are less prevalent among residents of the city and inner suburbs and among younger people; they are more common in the outer suburbs and among older people.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] At the same time, some residents of the city speak in Southern variations of African-American English.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta has a diverse lesbian, gay, bisexual, and transgender (LGBT) population.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] According to a 2006 survey by the Williams Institute, Atlanta ranked third among major American cities, behind San Francisco and slightly behind Seattle, with 12.8% of the city's total population identifying as LGB.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The Midtown and Cheshire Bridge areas have historically been the epicenters of LGBT culture in Atlanta.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta formed a reputation for being a place inclusive to LGBT people after former mayor Ivan Allen Jr. dubbed it "the city too busy to hate" in the 1960s (referring to racial relations).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta has consistently scored 100% on the Human Rights Campaign's Municipal Equality Index that measures how inclusive a city's laws, policies and services are for LGBT people who live or work there.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Religion in Atlanta, while historically centered on Protestant Christianity, now encompasses many faiths, as a result of the city and metro area's increasingly international population.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Some 63% of residents identified as some type of Protestant according to the Pew Research Center in 2014, but in recent decades the Roman Catholic Church has increased in numbers and influence because of new migrants to the region.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Metro Atlanta also has numerous ethnic or national Christian congregations, including Korean and Indian churches.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The larger non-Christian faiths according to both studies are Judaism, Islam, and Hinduism.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Overall, there are over 1,000 places of worship within Atlanta.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] With a GDP of $385 billion, the Atlanta metropolitan area's economy is the 8th-largest in the country and the 15th-largest in the world.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Corporate operations play a major role in Atlanta's economy, as the city claims the nation's third-largest concentration of Fortune 500 companies (tied for third with Chicago).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Over 75% of Fortune 1000 companies conduct business operations in the city's metro area, and the region hosts offices of over 1,250 multinational corporations.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Many corporations are drawn to the city by its educated workforce; as of 2014, 45% of adults aged 25 or older residing in the city have at least four-year college degrees, compared to the national average of 28%.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta was born as a railroad town, and logistics continue to represent an important part of the city's economy to this day.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In 2021, major freight railroad Norfolk Southern moved their headquarters to Atlanta, and the city hosts major classification yards for Norfolk Southern and CSX.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Hartsfield–Jackson Atlanta International Airport is the world's busiest airport, and the headquarters of Delta Air Lines.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Delta operates the world's largest airline hub at Hartsfield-Jackson and is metro Atlanta's largest employer.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] UPS, the world's largest courier company, operates an air cargo hub at Hartsfield-Jackson, and has their headquarters in neighboring Sandy Springs.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Media is also an important aspect of Atlanta's economy.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] In the 1980s, media mogul Ted Turner founded the Cable News Network (CNN), Turner Network Television (TNT), HLN (HLN), Turner Classic Movies (TCM), The Cartoon Network, Inc. and its namesake television network, TruTV (truTV) and the Turner Broadcasting System (TBS) in the city.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Around the same time, Cox Enterprises, now the nation's third-largest cable television service and the publisher of over a dozen American newspapers, moved its headquarters to the city.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Notable sports networks headquartered in Atlanta include TNT Sports, NBA TV, Bally Sports South, and Bally Sports Southeast.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The Weather Channel is also based just outside of the city in suburban Cobb County.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Information technology (IT) has become an increasingly important part of Atlanta's economic output, earning the city the nickname the "Silicon peach".
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] As of 2013, Atlanta contains the fourth-largest concentration of IT jobs in the U.S., numbering 85,000+.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The city is also ranked as the sixth fastest-growing for IT jobs, with an employment growth of 4.8% in 2012 and a three-year growth near 9%, or 16,000 jobs.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Companies are drawn to Atlanta's lower costs and educated workforce.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Recently, Atlanta has been the center for film and television production, largely because of the Georgia Entertainment Industry Investment Act, which awards qualified productions a transferable income tax credit of 20% of all in-state costs for film and television investments of $500,000 or more.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Film and television production facilities based in Atlanta include Techwood Studios, Pinewood Atlanta Studios, Tyler Perry Studios, Williams Street Productions, and the Cinespace Film Studios soundstages.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Film and television production injected $9.5 billion into Georgia's economy in 2017, with Atlanta garnering most of the projects.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] Atlanta has emerged as the all-time most popular destination for film production in the United States and one of the 10 most popular destinations globally.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] As of 2026, Atlanta was designated the best city in the nation for young professionals to start a career using two categories: professional opportunities and quality of life.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p01] The city was also ranked 12th best for starting a new business.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta has drawn residents from many other parts of the U.S., in addition to many recent immigrants to the U.S. who have made the metropolitan area their home, establishing Atlanta as the cultural and economic hub of an increasingly multi-cultural metropolitan area.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] This unique cultural combination reveals itself in the arts district of Midtown, the quirky neighborhoods on the city's eastside, and the multi-ethnic enclaves found along Buford Highway.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta is one of few United States cities with permanent, professional, and resident companies in all major performing arts disciplines: opera (Atlanta Opera), ballet (Atlanta Ballet), orchestral music (Atlanta Symphony Orchestra), and theater (the Alliance Theatre).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta attracts many touring Broadway acts, concerts, shows, and exhibitions catering to a variety of interests.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta's performing arts district is concentrated in Midtown Atlanta at the Woodruff Arts Center, which is home to the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra and the Alliance Theatre.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city frequently hosts touring Broadway acts, especially at The Fox Theatre, a historic landmark among the highest-grossing theaters of its size.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] As a national center for the arts, Atlanta is home to significant art museums and institutions.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The renowned High Museum of Art is arguably the South's leading art museum.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Museum of Design Atlanta (MODA) and the SCAD FASH Museum of Fashion + Film are the only such museums in the Southeast.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Contemporary art museums include the Atlanta Contemporary Art Center and the Museum of Contemporary Art of Georgia.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] A recent arts addition is known as The Warehouse, a storage facility that was turned into a world-class art gallery featuring more than 400 works of art collected over more than 40 years.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The collection is open to the public for free.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Institutions of higher education contribute to Atlanta's art scene, with the Savannah College of Art and Design's Atlanta campus providing the city's arts community with a steady stream of curators.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Carlos Museum contains the largest collection of ancient art in the Southeast.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Spelman College Museum of Fine Art is the only museum in the nation to focus on art by women of the African diaspora.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Williams Museum of Papermaking features the largest collection of paper and paper-related artifacts in the world.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta has become one of the U.S.'s best cities for street art in recent years.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] It is home to Living Walls, an annual street art conference and the Outerspace Project, an annual event series that merges public art, live music, design, action sports, and culture.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Examples of street art in Atlanta can be found on the Atlanta Street Art Map.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta is home to the nationally known Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, whose music directors have included Robert Shaw (1967–1988), Yoel Levi (1988–2000), Robert Spano (2001–2021), and Nathalie Stutzmann (2022–present).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The orchestra presents a season-long series of concerts including prominent world soloists such as pianists Kirill Gerstein, Yeol Eum Son, Inon Barnatan, Lang Lang, Francesco Piemontesi, cellist Alisa Weilerstein, singer Andrea Bocelli and many others.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta has played a major or contributing role in the development of various genres of American music at different points in the city's history.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Beginning as early as the 1920s, Atlanta emerged as a center for country music, which was brought to the city by migrants from Appalachia.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] During the countercultural 1960s, Atlanta hosted the Atlanta International Pop Festival, with the 1969 festival taking place more than a month before Woodstock and featuring many of the same bands.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] During the 1980s, Atlanta had an active punk rock scene centered on two of the city's music venues, 688 Club and the Metroplex, and Atlanta famously played host to the Sex Pistols' first U.S. show, which was performed at the Great Southeastern Music Hall.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The 1990s saw the city produce major mainstream acts across many different musical genres.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Country music artist Travis Tritt, and R&B sensations Xscape, TLC, Usher and Toni Braxton, were just some of the musicians who call Atlanta home.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In the 2000s, Atlanta was recognized by the Brooklyn-based *Vice* magazine for its indie rock scene, which revolves around the various live music venues found on the city's alternative eastside.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] To facilitate further local development, the state government provides qualified businesses and productions a 15% transferable income tax credit for in-state costs of music investments.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] As the national leader for motion picture and television production, and a top ten global leader, Atlanta plays a significant role in the entertainment industry.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta is home to the Tyler Perry Studios which is one of the largest film production studios in the U.S.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] It was announced in 2022 a film about the 1956 Sugar Bowl and '56 Atlanta riots would be produced here.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta's festival season stretches from January through November.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta has more festivals than any city in the southeastern United States.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] As of 2010, Atlanta is the seventh-most visited city in the United States, with over 35 million visitors per year.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Although the most popular attraction among visitors to Atlanta is the Georgia Aquarium, and until 2012, the world's largest indoor aquarium, Atlanta's tourism industry is mostly driven by the city's history museums and outdoor attractions.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta contains a notable number of historical museums and sites, including the Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] National Historical Park, which includes the preserved childhood home of Dr.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] President Jimmy Carter's papers and other material relating to the Carter administration and the Carter family's life; and the Margaret Mitchell House and Museum, where Mitchell wrote the best-selling novel *Gone with the Wind*.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta contains several outdoor attractions.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta Botanical Garden, adjacent to Piedmont Park, is home to the 600-foot-long (180 m) Kendeda Canopy Walk, a skywalk that allows visitors to tour one of the city's last remaining urban forests from 40 feet (12 m) above the ground.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Canopy Walk is the only canopy-level pathway of its kind in the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Zoo Atlanta, in Grant Park, accommodates over 1,300 animals representing more than 220 species.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Home to the nation's largest collections of gorillas and orangutans, the zoo is one of only four zoos in the U.S. to house giant pandas.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Festivals showcasing arts and crafts, film, and music, including the Atlanta Dogwood Festival, the Atlanta Film Festival, and Music Midtown, respectively, are also popular with tourists.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Tourists are drawn to the city's culinary scene, which comprises a mix of urban establishments garnering national attention, ethnic restaurants serving cuisine from every corner of the world, and traditional eateries specializing in Southern dining.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Since the turn of the 21st century, Atlanta has emerged as a sophisticated restaurant town.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Many restaurants opened in the city's gentrifying neighborhoods have received praise at the national level, including Bocado, Bacchanalia, and Miller Union in West Midtown, Empire State South in Midtown, and Two Urban Licks and Rathbun's on the east side.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2011, *The New York Times* characterized Empire State South and Miller Union as reflecting "a new kind of sophisticated Southern sensibility centered on the farm but experienced in the city".
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Visitors seeking to sample international Atlanta are directed to Buford Highway, the city's international corridor, and suburban Gwinnett County.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] There, the nearly-million immigrants that make Atlanta home have established various authentic ethnic restaurants representing virtually every nationality on the globe.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] For traditional Southern fare, one of the city's most famous establishments is The Varsity, a long-lived fast food chain and the world's largest drive-in restaurant.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Mary Mac's Tea Room and Paschal's are more formal destinations for Southern food.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta is best known for its barbecue, hamburgers, Southern fried chicken, and lemon pepper wings.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Buford Highway (immediately northeast of Atlanta) is home to many authentic ethnic cuisines such as Mexican and Asian foods.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta's culinary landscape is highlighted by its inclusion in the prestigious Michelin Guide, featuring several restaurants recognized for their exceptional cuisine and premier dining destination in the Southeast.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta's rapidly expanding food scene is marked by a notable diversity, particularly with the increasing variety and number of Indian restaurants across the city and its metropolitan area, including Chai Pani, a Michelin Guide restaurant.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Sports are an important part of the culture of Atlanta.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city is home to professional franchises for four major team sports: the Atlanta Braves of Major League Baseball, the Atlanta Hawks of the National Basketball Association, the Atlanta Falcons of the National Football League, and Atlanta United FC of Major League Soccer.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In addition, many of the city's universities participate in collegiate sports.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city also regularly hosts international, professional, and collegiate sporting events.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Originally established as the Boston Red Stockings in 1871, they are the oldest continually operating professional sports franchise in the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Braves franchise overall has won eighteen National League pennants and four World Series championships in three different cities, with their first in 1914 as the Boston Braves, in 1957 as the Milwaukee Braves, and in 1995 and 2021 as the Atlanta Braves.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The 1995 title occurred during an unprecedented run of 14 straight divisional championships from 1991 to 2005.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The team plays at Truist Park, having moved from Turner Field for the 2017 season.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The new stadium is outside the city limits, located 10 miles (16 km) northwest of downtown in the Cumberland/Galleria area of Cobb County.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta Falcons have played in Atlanta since their inception in 1966.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The team plays its home games at Mercedes-Benz Stadium, having moved from the Georgia Dome in 2017.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] They have been unsuccessful in both of their Super Bowl trips, losing to the Denver Broncos in Super Bowl XXXIII in 1999 and to the New England Patriots in Super Bowl LI in 2017, the largest comeback in Super Bowl history.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2019, Atlanta also briefly hosted an Alliance of American Football team, the Atlanta Legends, but the league was suspended during its first season and the team folded.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta Hawks were founded in 1946 as the Tri-Cities Blackhawks, playing in Moline, Illinois.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Louis in 1968 and play their games in State Farm Arena.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta Dream of the Women's National Basketball Association shared an arena with the Hawks for most of their existence; however the WNBA team moved to a smaller arena in the southern Atlanta suburb of College Park in 2021.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Professional soccer has been played in some form in Atlanta since 1967.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta's first professional soccer team was the Atlanta Chiefs of the original North American Soccer League, which won the 1968 NASL Championship and defeated English first division club Manchester City F.C. twice in international friendlies.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 1998, the Atlanta Silverbacks were formed, playing the new North American Soccer League.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] They now play as an amateur club in the National Premier Soccer League.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2017, Atlanta United FC began play as Atlanta's first premier-division professional soccer club since the Chiefs.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] They won MLS Cup 2018, defeating the Portland Timbers 2–0.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Fan reception has been very positive; the team has broken several single-game and season attendance records for both MLS and the U.S.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The club is estimated by Forbes to be the most valuable club in Major League Soccer.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The United States Soccer Federation moved their headquarters from Chicago to Atlanta in 2023 with the help of Falcons and Atlanta United owner Arthur Blank, with the new training center bearing his name.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta will receive a NWSL team in 2028.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In ice hockey, Atlanta has had two National Hockey League franchises, both of which relocated to a city in Canada after playing in Atlanta for fewer than 15 years.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta Flames (now the Calgary Flames) played from 1972 to 1980, and the Atlanta Thrashers (now the Winnipeg Jets) played from 1999 to 2011.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta Gladiators, a minor league hockey team in the ECHL, have played in the Atlanta suburb of Duluth since 2003.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The ASUN Conference moved its headquarters to Atlanta in 2019.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Several other emerging sports also have professional franchises in Atlanta.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Georgia Swarm compete in the National Lacrosse League.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta Vibe compete in the Pro Volleyball Federation.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta has long been known as the "capital" of college football in America.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] It is home to four-time national champion Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football and the Georgia State Panthers.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Other annual college football events include the Aflac Kickoff Game, the Celebration Bowl, the MEAC/SWAC Challenge, and the Chick-fil-A Peach Bowl which is one of College Football's major New Year's Six Bowl games and a College Football Playoff bowl.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta additionally hosted the 2018 College Football Playoff National Championship and eventually would the host the 2025 event in the city as well.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta regularly hosts a variety of sporting events.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Most famous was the Centennial 1996 Summer Olympics.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city has hosted the Super Bowl three times: Super Bowl XXVIII in 1994, Super Bowl XXXIV in 2000, and Super Bowl LIII in 2019.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In professional golf, The Tour Championship, the final PGA Tour event of the season, is played annually at East Lake Golf Club.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2001 and 2011, Atlanta hosted the PGA Championship, one of the four major championships in men's professional golf, at the Atlanta Athletic Club.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2011, Atlanta hosted professional wrestling's annual WrestleMania.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In soccer, Atlanta has hosted numerous international friendlies and CONCACAF Gold Cup matches.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city has hosted the NCAA Final Four Men's Basketball Championship five times, most recently in 2020.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta will serve as one of the eleven US host cities for the 2026 FIFA World Cup.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Every summer, Atlanta hosts the Atlanta Open, a men's professional tennis tournament.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Running is a popular local sport, and the city declares itself to be "Running City USA".
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city hosts the Peachtree Road Race, the world's largest 10 km race, annually on Independence Day.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta also hosts the nation's largest Thanksgiving day half marathon, which starts and ends at Center Parc Stadium.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta Marathon, which starts and ends at Centennial Olympic Park, routes through many of the city's historic landmarks.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta's 343 parks, nature preserves, and gardens cover 3,622 acres (14.66 km2), which amounts to only 5.6% of the city's total acreage, compared to the national average of just over 10%.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] However, 77% of Atlantans live within a 10-minute walk of a park, a percentage slightly better than the national average of 76%.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In its 2023 ParkScore ranking, The Trust for Public Land reported that among the park systems of the 100 most populous U.S. cities, Atlanta's park system received a ranking of 28.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Piedmont Park, in Midtown, is Atlanta's most iconic green space.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The park, which underwent a major renovation and expansion in recent years, attracts visitors from across the region and hosts cultural events throughout the year.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Shirley Clarke Franklin Park, a 280-acre green space and reservoir, opened in 2021 and is the city's largest park.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Chattahoochee River National Recreation Area, in the northwestern corner of the city, preserves a 48 mi (77 km) stretch of the river for public recreation opportunities.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta Botanical Garden, adjacent to Piedmont Park, contains formal gardens, including a Japanese garden and a rose garden, woodland areas, and a conservatory that includes indoor exhibits of plants from tropical rainforests and deserts.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Beltline, a former rail corridor that forms a 22 mi (35 km) loop around Atlanta's core, has been transformed into a series of parks, connected by a multi-use trail, increasing Atlanta's park space by 40%.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta offers resources and opportunities for amateur and participatory sports and recreation.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Golf and tennis are popular in Atlanta, and the city contains six public golf courses and 182 tennis courts.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Facilities along the Chattahoochee River cater to watersports enthusiasts, providing the opportunity for kayaking, canoeing, fishing, boating, or tubing.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city's only skate park, a 15,000 square feet (1,400 m2) facility that offers bowls, curbs, and smooth-rolling concrete mounds, is at Historic Fourth Ward Park.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta has a reputation as a "city in a forest" due to an abundance of trees that is rare among major cities.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city's main street is named after a tree, and beyond the Downtown, Midtown, and Buckhead business districts, the skyline gives way to a dense canopy of woods that spreads into the suburbs.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city is home to the Atlanta Dogwood Festival, an annual arts and crafts festival held one weekend during early April, when the native dogwoods are in bloom.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The nickname is factually accurate, as vegetation covers 47.9% of the city as of 2017, the highest among all major American cities, and well above the national average of 27%.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta's tree coverage does not go unnoticed—it was the main reason cited by *National Geographic* in naming Atlanta a "Place of a Lifetime".
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city's lush tree canopy, which filters out pollutants and cools sidewalks and buildings, has increasingly been under assault from man and nature due to heavy rains, drought, aged forests, new pests, and urban construction.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] A 2001 study found Atlanta's heavy tree cover declined from 48% in 1974 to 38% in 1996.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Community organizations and the city government are addressing the problem.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Trees Atlanta, a non-profit organization founded in 1985, has planted and distributed over 113,000 shade trees in the city, and Atlanta's government has awarded $130,000 in grants to neighborhood groups to plant trees.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Fees are additionally imposed on developers that remove trees on their property per a citywide ordinance, active since 1993.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta is governed by a mayor and the 15-member Atlanta City Council.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city council consists of one member from each of the city's 12 districts and three at-large members.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The mayor may veto a bill passed by the council, but the council can override the veto with a two-thirds majority.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The mayor of Atlanta is Andre Dickens, a Democrat elected on a nonpartisan ballot whose first term in office began on January 3, 2022.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Every mayor elected since 1973 has been Black.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2001, Shirley Franklin became the first woman to be elected mayor of Atlanta, and the first African-American woman to serve as mayor of a major Southern city.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta city politics suffered from a notorious reputation for corruption during the 1990s administration of Mayor Bill Campbell, who was convicted by a federal jury in 2006 on three counts of tax evasion in connection with gambling winnings during trips he took with city contractors.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] As the state capital, Atlanta is the site of most of Georgia's state government.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Georgia State Capitol building, located downtown, houses the offices of the governor, lieutenant governor, and secretary of state, as well as the General Assembly.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Governor's Mansion is in a residential section of Buckhead.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta serves as the regional hub for many arms of the federal bureaucracy, including the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The City of Atlanta annexed the CDC into its territory effective January 1, 2018.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta also plays an important role in the federal judiciary system, containing the United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit and the United States District Court for the Northern District of Georgia.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Historically, Atlanta has been a stronghold for the Democratic Party.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Although municipal elections are officially nonpartisan, nearly all of the city's elected officials are registered Democrats.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city is split among 14 state house districts and four state senate districts, all held by Democrats.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] At the federal level, Atlanta is split between three congressional districts.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Most of the city is in the 5th district, represented by Democrat Nikema Williams.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Much of southern Atlanta is in the 13th district, whose seat is currently vacant following the death of Democrat David Scott.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] A small portion in the north is in the 11th district, represented by Republican Barry Loudermilk.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city is served by the Atlanta Police Department (APD), which numbers 2,000 officers and oversaw a 40% decrease in the city's crime rate between 2001 and 2009.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2012, *Forbes* ranked Atlanta as the 6th most dangerous American city, but by 2023, the city dropped out of its top 10.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Despite some improvement in crime, street gangs have continued to plague the city since the 1980s.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2022, there was a 200% increase in gang-related charges in the city.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2023, Money Inc named Atlanta the third worst gang city in the U.S.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Also in 2023, it was estimated that about 1,000 gangs in the Atlanta area were responsible for at least 70% of all crime including identity theft, credit card fraud, drug trafficking, and human trafficking.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Georgia Bureau of Investigation Gang Task Force in partnership with the APD is leading efforts in dismantling gang activity and arresting culprits.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta Fire Rescue Department provides fire protection and first responder emergency medical services to the city from its 35 fire stations.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2017, AFRD responded to over 100,000 calls for service over a coverage area of 135.7 square miles (351.5 square kilometers).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The department also protects Hartsfield–Jackson with five fire stations on the property, serving over 1 million passengers from over 100 countries.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The department protects over 3000 high-rise buildings, 23 miles (37 kilometers) of the rapid rail system, and 60 miles (97 kilometers) of interstate highway.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Georgia National Guard is based in the city.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Emergency ambulance services are provided to city residents by hospital-based Grady EMS (Fulton County), and American Medical Response (DeKalb County).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In January 2017, Atlanta declared itself a "welcoming city" and "will remain open and welcoming to all".
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Nonetheless, Atlanta does not consider itself to be a "sanctuary city".
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta Mayor Keisha Lance Bottoms said: "Our city does not support ICE.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] We don't have a relationship with the U.S.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2025, Atlanta Public Safety Training Center opened a $118 million training center for police and firefighters.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] With more than 15 colleges and universities, including three law schools and two medical schools, Atlanta is considered one of the nation's largest hubs for higher education.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Three universities have earned the highest classification of "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity".
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Georgia Institute of Technology, commonly referred to as Georgia Tech, is a prominent public research university in Midtown.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] It offers highly ranked degree programs in engineering, design, industrial management, the sciences, business, and architecture.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta is home to nationally renowned private colleges and universities, most notably Emory University, a leading liberal arts and research institution that operates Emory Healthcare, the largest health care system in Georgia.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The City of Atlanta annexed Emory into its territory effective January 1, 2018.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta University Center is also in the city; it is the nation's only contiguous consortium of historically black colleges, comprising Spelman College, Clark Atlanta University, Morehouse College, and Morehouse School of Medicine.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta contains a campus of the Savannah College of Art and Design, a private art and design university that has proven to be a major factor in the recent growth of Atlanta's visual art community.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta also boasts American Bar Association accredited law schools: Atlanta's John Marshall Law School, Emory University School of Law, and Georgia State University College of Law.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The University of Georgia's Terry College of Business operates a satellite campus in Atlanta's Buckhead district, a major financial center in the city.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] This location facilitates Executive and Professional MBA programs plus executive education offerings.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Buckhead campus also serves as a hub where Terry students, alumni, faculty, and staff can engage with the business community.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta Regional Council of Higher Education (ARCHE) is dedicated to strengthening synergy among 19 public and private colleges and universities in the Atlanta region.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Participating Atlanta region colleges and universities partner on joint-degree programs, cross-registration, library services, and cultural events.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Approximately 49,000 students are enrolled in 106 schools in Atlanta Public Schools (APS), some of which are operated as charter schools.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2018, the City of Atlanta annexed a portion of DeKalb County containing the Centers for Disease Control and Emory University; this portion was to be zoned to the DeKalb County School District until 2024, when it was to transition into APS.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2017 the number of children living in the annexed territory who attended public schools was nine.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The primary network-affiliated television stations in Atlanta are WSB-TV 2 (ABC), WAGA-TV 5 (Fox)., WXIA-TV 11 (NBC), WPXA-TV 14 (Ion), WPCH-TV 17, (CW), WUVG-TV 34 (Univision/UniMás), WATL 36 (MyNetworkTV), WANF 46 (Independent), WKTB-CD 47 (Telemundo) and WUPA 69 (CBS).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta metropolitan area is served by two public television stations (both PBS member stations) and two public radio stations.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] WGTV 8 is the flagship station of the statewide Georgia Public Television network, while WABE-TV 30 is owned by Atlanta Public Schools.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Georgia Public Radio is listener-funded and comprises one NPR member station, WABE, a classical music station also operated by Atlanta Public Schools.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The second public radio, listener-funded NPR member station is WCLK, a jazz music station owned and operated by Clark Atlanta University.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta is served by *The Atlanta Journal-Constitution*, its only major daily newspaper with wide distribution (the *AJC* stopped publishing a physical newspaper in 2026 in favor of digital coverage).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The *Atlanta Journal-Constitution* is the result of a 1950 merger between *The Atlanta Journal* and *The Atlanta Constitution*, with staff consolidation occurring in 1982 and separate publication of the morning *Constitution* and afternoon *Journal* ceasing in 2001.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Alternative weekly newspapers include *Creative Loafing*, which has a weekly print circulation of 80,000.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] *Atlanta Daily World* is the oldest Black newspaper in Atlanta and one of the earliest Black newspapers in American history.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] *Atlanta* magazine is a monthly general-interest magazine based in and covering Atlanta.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta has a network of freeways that radiate out from the city, and automobiles are the dominant means of transportation in the region.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Three major interstate highways converge in Atlanta: I-20 (east-west), I-75 (northwest-southeast), and I-85 (northeast-southwest).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The latter two combine in the middle of the city to form the Downtown Connector (I-75/85), which carries more than 340,000 vehicles per day and is one of the most congested segments of interstate highway in the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta is mostly encircled by Interstate 285, a beltway locally known as "the Perimeter" that has come to mark the boundary between "Inside the Perimeter" (ITP), the city and close-in suburbs, and "Outside the Perimeter" (OTP), the outer suburbs and exurbs.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The heavy reliance on automobiles for transportation in Atlanta has resulted in traffic, commute, and air pollution rates that rank among the worst in the country.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The City of Atlanta has a higher than average percentage of households without a car.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2015, 15.2 percent of Atlanta households lacked a car, and this percentage increased slightly to 16.4 percent in 2016.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Atlanta averaged 1.31 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority (MARTA) provides public transportation in the form of buses, heavy rail, and a downtown light rail loop.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Notwithstanding heavy automotive usage in Atlanta, the city's subway system is the eighth busiest in the country.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] MARTA rail lines connect key destinations, such as the airport, Downtown, Midtown, Buckhead, and Perimeter Center.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] However, significant destinations, such as Emory University and Cumberland, remain unserved.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] As a result, a 2011 Brookings Institution study placed Atlanta 91st of 100 metro areas for transit accessibility.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Emory University operates its Cliff shuttle buses with 200,000 boardings per month, while private minibuses supply Buford Highway.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Amtrak, the national rail passenger system, provides service to Atlanta via the *Crescent train* (New York–New Orleans), which stops at Peachtree Station.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2014, the Atlanta Streetcar opened to the public.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The streetcar's line, which is also known as the Downtown Loop, runs 2.7 miles (4.3 km) around the downtown tourist areas of Peachtree Center, Centennial Olympic Park, the Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] National Historical Park, and Sweet Auburn.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The Atlanta Streetcar line is also being expanded on in the coming years to include a wider range of Atlanta's neighborhoods and important places of interest, with a total of over 50 miles (80 km) of track in the plan.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Hartsfield–Jackson Atlanta International Airport is the world's busiest airport as measured by passenger traffic and aircraft traffic.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The facility offers air service to over 150 U.S. destinations and more than 75 international destinations in 50 countries, with over 2,500 arrivals and departures daily.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Delta Air Lines maintains its largest hub at the airport.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Situated 10 miles (16 km) south of downtown in Clayton and Fulton counties, the airport covers most of the land inside a wedge formed by Interstate 75, Interstate 85, and Interstate 285.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Cycling is a growing mode of transportation in Atlanta, more than doubling since 2009, when it comprised 1.1% of all commutes (up from 0.3% in 2000).
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Although Atlanta's lack of bike lanes and hilly topography may deter many residents from cycling, the city's transportation plan calls for the construction of 226 miles (364 km) of bike lanes by 2020, with the Beltline helping to achieve this goal.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] In 2012, Atlanta's first "bike track" was constructed on 10th Street in Midtown.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The two-lane bike track runs from Monroe Drive west to Charles Allen Drive, with connections to the Beltline and Piedmont Park.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] Starting in June 2016, Atlanta received a bike sharing program, known as Relay Bike Share, with 100 bikes in Downtown and Midtown, which expanded to 500 bikes at 65 stations as of April 2017.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] According to the 2016 American Community Survey (five-year average), 68.6% of working city of Atlanta residents commuted by driving alone, 7% carpooled, 10% used public transportation, and 4.6% walked.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] About 2.1% used all other forms of transportation, including taxi, bicycle, and motorcycle.
[src:cinnaholic/atlanta-georgia-p02] The city has also become one of a handful of "scooter capitals", where companies like Lime and Bird have gained a major foothold by placing electric scooters on street corners and byways.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is home to the oldest campus in the University of California, the University of California, Berkeley, and the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, which is managed and operated by the university.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] It also has the Graduate Theological Union, one of the largest religious studies institutions in the world.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is considered one of the most socially progressive cities in the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The site of today's City of Berkeley was the territory of the Chochenyo/Huchiun Ohlone people when the first Europeans arrived.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Human remains and skeletons from Native American burials have been unearthed in West Berkeley and on campus alongside Strawberry Creek.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Other artifacts were discovered in the 1950s in the downtown area during remodeling of a commercial building, near the upper course of the creek.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The first people of European descent (most of whom were of mixed race and born in America) arrived with the De Anza Expedition in 1776.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The De Anza Expedition led to establishment of the Spanish Presidio of San Francisco at the entrance to San Francisco Bay (the "Golden Gate)." Luis Peralta was among the soldiers at the Presidio.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] For his services to the King of Spain, he was granted a vast stretch of land on the east shore of San Francisco Bay (the *contra costa*, "opposite shore") for a ranch, including that portion that now comprises the City of Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Luis Peralta named his holding "Rancho San Antonio." The primary activity of the ranch was raising cattle for meat and hides, but hunting and farming were also pursued.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Eventually, Peralta gave portions of the ranch to each of his four sons.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] What is now Berkeley lies mostly in the portion that went to Peralta's son Domingo, with a little in the portion that went to another son, Vicente.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] No artifact survives of the Domingo or Vicente ranches, but their names survive in Berkeley street names (Vicente, Domingo, and Peralta).
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] However, legal title to all land in the City of Berkeley remains based on the original Peralta land grant.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The Peraltas' Rancho San Antonio continued after Alta California passed from Spanish to Mexican sovereignty following the Mexican War of Independence.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] However, the advent of U.S. sovereignty after the Mexican–American War, and especially, the gold rush, saw the Peraltas' lands quickly encroached on by squatters and diminished by dubious legal proceedings.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The lands of the brothers Domingo and Vicente were quickly reduced to reservations close to their respective ranch homes.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The rest of the land was surveyed and parceled out to various American claimants (*See* Kellersberger's Map).
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Politically, the area that became Berkeley was initially part of a vast Contra Costa County.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] On March 25, 1853, Alameda County was created from a partition of Contra Costa County, as well as from a small portion of Santa Clara County.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The area that became Berkeley was then the northern part of the "Oakland Township" subdivision of Alameda County.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] During this period, "Berkeley" was mostly a mix of open land, farms, and ranches, with a small, though busy, wharf by the bay.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1866, Oakland's private College of California looked for a new site.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] It settled on a location north of Oakland along the foot of the Contra Costa Range (later called the Berkeley Hills) on Strawberry Creek, at an elevation of about 500 feet (150 m) above the bay, commanding a view of the Bay Area and the Pacific Ocean through the Golden Gate.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] According to the *Centennial Record of the University of California*, "In 1866, at Founders' Rock, a group of College of California men watched two ships standing out to sea through the Golden Gate.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The College of California's College Homestead Association planned to raise funds for the new campus by selling off adjacent parcels of land.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] To this end, they laid out a plat and street grid that became the basis of Berkeley's modern street plan.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Their plans fell far short of their desires, and they began a collaboration with the State of California that culminated in 1868 with the creation of the public University of California.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] As construction began on the new site, more residences were constructed in the vicinity of the new campus.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] At the same time, a settlement of residences, saloons, and various industries grew around the wharf area called Ocean View.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] A horsecar ran from Temescal in Oakland to the university campus along what is now Telegraph Avenue.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] By the 1870s, the transcontinental railroad reached its terminus in Oakland.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1876, a branch line of the Central Pacific Railroad, the Berkeley Branch Railroad, was laid from a junction with the mainline called Shellmound (now a part of Emeryville) into what is now downtown Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] That same year, the mainline of the transcontinental railroad into Oakland was re-routed, putting the right-of-way along the bay shore through Ocean View.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] There was a strong prohibition movement in Berkeley at this time.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1876, the state enacted the "mile limit law", which forbade sale or public consumption of alcohol within one mile (1.6 km) of the new University of California.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Then, in 1899, Berkeley residents voted to make their city an alcohol-free zone.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Scientists, scholars and religious leaders spoke vehemently of the dangers of alcohol.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] On April 1, 1878, the people of Ocean View and the area around the university campus, together with local farmers, were granted incorporation by the State of California as the Town of Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The first elected trustees of the town were the slate of Denis Kearney's anti-Chinese Workingman's Party, who were particularly favored in the working-class area of the former Ocean View, now called West Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] During the 1880s Berkeley had segregated housing and anti-Chinese laws.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The area near the university became known for a time as East Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Due to the influence of the university, the modern age came quickly to Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Electric lights and the telephone were in use by 1888.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Electric streetcars soon replaced the horsecar.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] A silent film of one of these early streetcars in Berkeley can be seen at the Library of Congress website.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley's slow growth ended abruptly with the Great San Francisco earthquake of 1906.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The town and other parts of the East Bay escaped serious damage, and thousands of refugees flowed across the Bay.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Among them were most of San Francisco's painters and sculptors, who between 1907 and 1911 created one of the largest art colonies west of Chicago.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Cannon described the founding of the Berkeley Art Association and the rivalries of competing studios and art clubs.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1908, a statewide referendum that proposed moving the California state capital to Berkeley was defeated by a margin of about 33,000 votes.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The city had named streets around the proposed capitol grounds for California counties.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] They bear those names today, a legacy of the failed referendum.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] On March 4, 1909, following public referendums, the citizens of Berkeley were granted a new charter by the State of California, and the Town of Berkeley became the City of Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Rapid growth continued up to the crash of 1929.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The Great Depression hit Berkeley hard, but not as hard as many other places in the U.S., thanks in part to the university.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1916, Berkeley implemented single-family zoning as an effort to keep minorities out of white neighborhoods.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] This has been described as the first implementation of single-family zoning in the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] By 2021, nearly half of Berkeley's residential neighborhoods were still exclusively zoned for single-family homes.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 2025, Berkeley legalized small multi-family buildings in most of the city.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] On September 17, 1923, a major fire swept down the hills toward the university campus and the downtown section.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Around 640 structures burned before a late-afternoon sea breeze stopped its progress, allowing firefighters to put it out.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The next big growth occurred with the advent of World War II, when large numbers of people moved to the Bay Area to work in the many war industries, such as the immense Kaiser Shipyards in nearby Richmond.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] One who moved out, but played a big role in the outcome of the war, was U.C. professor and Berkeley resident J.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] During the war, an Army base, Camp Ashby, was temporarily sited in Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The element berkelium was synthesized utilizing the 60-inch (1.5 m) cyclotron at UC Berkeley, and named in 1949, in recognition of the university, thus placing the city's name in the list of elements.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] During the 1940s, many African Americans migrated to Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1950, the Census Bureau reported Berkeley's population as 11.7% black and 84.6% white.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The postwar years brought moderate growth to the city, as events on the U.C. campus began to build up to the recognizable activism of the sixties.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In the 1950s, McCarthyism induced the university to demand a loyalty oath from its professors, many of whom refused to sign the oath on the principle of freedom of thought.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] House committee (HUAC) came to San Francisco to investigate the influence of communists in the Bay Area.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Their presence was met by protesters, including many from the university.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Meanwhile, a number of U.C. students became active in the civil rights movement.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Finally, in 1964, the university provoked a massive student protest by banning distribution of political literature on campus.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] This protest became the Free Speech Movement.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] As the Vietnam War rapidly escalated in the ensuing years, so did student activism at the university, particularly that organized by the Vietnam Day Committee.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is strongly identified with the rapid social changes, civic unrest, and political upheaval that characterized the mid-to-late 1960s.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In that period, Berkeley—especially Telegraph Avenue—became a focal point for the hippie movement, which spilled over the Bay from San Francisco.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Many hippies were apolitical drop-outs, rather than students, but in the heady atmosphere of Berkeley in 1967–1969 there was considerable overlap between the hippie movement and the radical left.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] An iconic event in the Berkeley Sixties scene was a conflict over a parcel of university property south of the contiguous campus site that came to be called "People's Park".
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The battle over the disposition of People's Park resulted in a month-long occupation of Berkeley by the National Guard on orders of then-Governor Ronald Reagan.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In the end, the park remained undeveloped, and remained so for decades.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] A spin-off, *People's Park Annex*, was established at the same time by activist citizens of Berkeley on a strip of land above the Bay Area Rapid Transit ("BART") underground construction along Hearst Avenue northwest of the U.C. campus.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The land had also been intended for development, but was turned over to the city by BART and is now Ohlone Park.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The era of large public protest in Berkeley waned considerably with the end of the Vietnam War in 1975.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] While the 1960s were the heyday of liberal activism in Berkeley, it remains one of the most overwhelmingly Democratic cities in the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] After the 1960s, Berkeley banned most new housing construction, in particular apartments.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Increasing enrollment at the university led to replacement of older buildings by large apartment buildings, especially in older parts of the city near the university and downtown.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Increasing enrollment also led the university to wanting to redevelop certain places of Berkeley, especially Southside, but more specifically People's Park.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Preservationists passed the Neighborhood Protection Ordinance in 1973 by ballot measure and the Landmarks Preservation Ordinance in 1974 by the City Council.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Together, these ordinances brought most new construction to a halt.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Facing rising housing costs, residents voted to enact rent control and vacancy control in 1980.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] For cities such as Berkeley, where rent control was already in place, the law limited the use of rent control to units built before the local rent-control law was enacted, i.e.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] During the 1970s and 1980s, activists increased their power in local government.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] This era also saw major developments in Berkeley's environmental and food culture.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley's last Republican mayor, Wallace J.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Alice Waters opened Chez Panisse in 1971.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The first curbside recycling program in the U.S. was started by the Ecology Center in 1973.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] As the city leaned more and more Democratic, local politics became divided between "Progressives" and "Moderates".
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] 1984 saw the Progressives take the majority for the first time.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Nancy Skinner became the first UC Berkeley student elected to City Council.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1986, in reaction to the 1984 election, a ballot measure switched Berkeley from at-large to district-based elections for city council.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1983, Berkeley's Domestic Partner Task Force was established, which in 1984 made policy recommendation to the school board, which passed domestic partner legislation.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The legislation became a model for similar measures nationwide.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1995, California's Costa–Hawkins Act ended vacancy control, allowing rents to increase when a tenant moved out.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Despite a slow down in 2005–2007, median home prices and rents remain dramatically higher than the rest of the nation, fueled by spillover from the San Francisco housing shortage and population growth.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] South and West Berkeley underwent gentrification, with some historically Black neighborhoods such as the Adeline Corridor seeing a 50% decline in Black / African American population from 1990 to 2010.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In the 1990s, public television's Frontline documentary series featured race relations at Berkeley's only public high school, Berkeley High School.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] With an economy dominated by the University of California and a high-demand housing market, Berkeley was relatively unaffected by the Great Recession.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] State budget cuts caused the university to increase the number of out-of-state and international students, with international enrollment, mostly from Asia, rising from 2,785 in 2007 to 5,951 in 2016.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Since then, more international restaurants have opened downtown and on Telegraph Avenue, including East Asian chains such as Ippudo and Daiso.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] A wave of downtown apartment construction began in 1998.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 2006, the Berkeley Oak Grove Protest began protesting construction of a new sports center annex to Memorial Stadium at the expense of a grove of oak trees on the UC campus.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The protest ended in September 2008 after a lengthy court process.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 2007–2008, Berkeley received media attention due to demonstrations against a Marine Corps recruiting office in downtown Berkeley and a series of controversial motions by Berkeley's city council regarding opposition to Marine recruiting.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] During the fall of 2010, the Berkeley Student Food Collective opened after many protests on the UC Berkeley campus due to the proposed opening of the fast food chain Panda Express.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Students and community members worked together to open a collectively run grocery store right off of the UC Berkeley campus, where the community can buy local, seasonal, humane, and organic foods.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The Berkeley Student Food Collective still operates at 2440 Bancroft Way.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] On September 18, 2012, Berkeley became what may be the first city in the U.S. to officially proclaim a day recognizing bisexuals: September 23, which is known as Celebrate Bisexuality Day.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] On September 2, 2014, the city council approved a measure to provide free medical marijuana to low-income patients.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The Measure D soda tax was approved by Berkeley voters on November 4, 2014, the first such tax in the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In the fall of 2011, the nationwide Occupy Wall Street movement came to two Berkeley locations: on the campus of the University of California and as an encampment in Civic Center Park.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] During a Black Lives Matter protest on December 6, 2014, police use of tear gas and batons to clear protesters from Telegraph Avenue led to a riot and five consecutive days and nights of protests, marches, and freeway occupations in Berkeley and Oakland.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Afterwards, changes were implemented by the Police Department to avoid escalation of violence and to protect bystanders during protests.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] During a protest against bigotry and U.S.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] President Donald Trump in August 2017, self-described anti-fascist protesters attacked Trump supporters in attendance.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Sometimes called "antifa", these ‘anti-fascist’ activists were clad in black shirts and other black attire, while some carried shields and others had masks or bandanas hiding their faces to help them evade capture after street fighting.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] These protests spanned February to September 2017 (See more at 2017 Berkeley Protests).
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 2019, protesters took up residence in People's Park against tree-chopping and were arrested by police in riot gear.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Many activists saw this as the university preparing to develop the park.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The city of Berkeley has historically been a central location for homeless communities in the Bay Area.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The city has passed ordinances to oust homeless individuals from Berkeley on multiple occasions.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Despite efforts to improve social services and remove unhoused individuals from the streets, homelessness has continued to be a significant problem in Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] A culture of anti-establishment and sociopolitical activism marked the 1960s.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The San Francisco Bay Area became a hotspot for hippie counterculture, and Berkeley became a haven for nonconformists and anarchists from all over the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Most public discourse around homelessness in Berkeley at this time was centered around the idea of street-living as an expression of counterculture.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Many non-student youth and adolescents sought alternative lifestyles and opted for voluntary homelessness during this time.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1969, People's Park was created and eventually became a haven for "small-time drug dealers, street people, and the homeless".
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Although the City of Berkeley has moved unhoused individuals from its streets, sometimes even relocating them to an unused landfill, People's Park has remained a safe space for them since its inception.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The park has become one of the few relatively safe spaces for homeless individuals to congregate in Berkeley and the greater Bay Area.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Stereotypes of homeless people as deviant individuals who chose to live vagrant lifestyles continued to color the discourse around street-dwellers in American cities.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] However, this time period was also characterized by a subtle shift in the perception of unhoused individuals.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The public began to realize that homelessness affected not only single men, but also women, children, and entire families.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] This recognition set the stage for the City of Berkeley's attitude towards homelessness in the next decade.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Organizations such as Building Opportunities for Self Sufficiency (BOSS) were established in 1971 in response to the needs of individuals with mental illness being released to the streets by state hospital closures.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In the 1990s, the City of Berkeley faced a substantial increase in the need for emergency housing shelters and saw a rise in the average amount of time individuals spent without stable housing.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] As housing became a more widespread problem, the general public, Berkeley City Council, and the University of California became increasingly anti-homeless in their opinions.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1994, Berkeley City Council considered the implementation of a set of anti-homeless laws that the *San Francisco Chronicle* described as being "among the strictest in the country".
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] These laws prohibited sitting, sleeping and begging in public spaces, and outlawed panhandling from people in a variety of contexts, such as sitting on public benches, buying a newspaper from a rack, or waiting in line for a movie.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In February 1995, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) sued the city for infringing free speech rights through its proposed anti-panhandling law.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The following month, the Street Spirit, a monthly newspaper written for and by people experiencing homelessness, published its first of hundreds of issues covering homelessness in the Bay Area and across the nation.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In May of that same year, a federal judge ruled that the anti-panhandling law did violate the First Amendment, but left the anti-sitting and sleeping laws untouched.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Following the implementation of these anti-sitting and sleeping ordinances in 1998, Berkeley increased its policing of homeless adults and youth, particularly in the shopping district surrounding Telegraph Avenue.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The mayor at that time, Shirley Dean, proposed a plan to increase both social support services for homeless youth and enforcement of anti-encampment laws.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Unhoused youth countered this plan with a request for the establishment of the city's first youth shelter, more trash cans, and more frequent cleaning of public bathrooms.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The City of Berkeley's 2017 annual homeless report and point-in-time count (PIT) estimate that on a given night, 972 people are homeless.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Sixty-eight percent (664 people) of these individuals are also unsheltered, living in places not considered suitable for human habitation, such as cars or streets.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Long-term homelessness in Berkeley is double the national average, with 27% of the city's homeless population facing chronic homelessness.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Chronic homelessness has been on the rise since 2015, and has been largely a consequence of the constrained local housing market.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 2015, rent in Alameda County increased by 25%, while the average household income only grew by 5%.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The City of Berkeley's 2017 report also estimated the number of unaccompanied youth in Berkeley at 189 individuals, 19% of the total homeless population in the city.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Homeless youth display greater risk of mental health issues, behavioral problems, and substance abuse, than any other homeless age group.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Furthermore, homeless youth identifying as LGBTQ+ are exposed to greater rates of physical and sexual abuse, and higher risk for sexually transmitted diseases, predominantly HIV.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The City of Berkeley has seen a consistent rise in the number of chronically homeless individuals over the past 30 years, and has implemented a number of different projects to reduce the number of people living on the streets.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 2008, the City focused its efforts on addressing chronic homelessness.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] This led to a 48% decline in the number of chronically homeless individuals reported in the 2009 Berkeley PIT.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] However, the number of "hidden homeless" individuals (those coping with housing insecurity by staying at a friend or relative's residence), increased significantly, likely in response to rising housing costs and costs of living.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 2012, the City considered measures that banned sitting in commercial areas throughout Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The measure was met with strong public opposition and did not pass.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] However, the City saw a strong need for it to implement rules addressing encampments and public usage of space as well as assessing the resources needed to assist the unhoused population.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In response to these needs the City of Berkeley established the Homeless Task Force, headed by then-Councilmember Jesse Arreguín.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Since its formation, the Task Force has proposed a number of different recommendations, from expanding the City Homeless Outreach and Mobile Crisis Teams, to building a short-term transitional shelter for unhoused individuals.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] According to the United States Census Bureau, the city's 17.7-square-mile (46 km2) area includes 10.5 square miles (27 km2) of land and 7.2 square miles (19 km2) (40.83%) water, most of it part of San Francisco Bay.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley borders the cities of Albany, Oakland, and Emeryville and Contra Costa County, including unincorporated Kensington, as well as San Francisco Bay.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley lies within telephone area code 510 (until September 2, 1991, Berkeley was part of the 415 telephone code that now covers only San Francisco and Marin counties), and the postal ZIP codes are 94701 through 94710, 94712, and 94720 for the University of California campus.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Most of Berkeley lies on a rolling sedimentary plain that rises gently from sea level to the base of the Berkeley Hills.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] East of the Hayward Fault along the base of the hills, elevation increases more rapidly.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The highest peak along the ridge line above Berkeley is Grizzly Peak, at an elevation of 1,754 feet (535 m).
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] A number of small creeks run from the hills to the Bay through Berkeley: Codornices, Schoolhouse, and Strawberry Creeks are the principal streams.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Most of these are largely culverted once they reach the plain west of the hills.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The Berkeley Hills are part of the Pacific Coast Ranges, and run in a northwest–southeast alignment.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Exposed in the Berkeley Hills are cherts and shales of the Claremont Formation (equivalent to the Monterey Formation), conglomerate and sandstone of the Orinda Formation and lava flows of the Moraga Volcanics.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Of similar age to the Moraga Volcanics (extinct), within the Northbrae neighborhood of Berkeley, are outcroppings of erosion resistant rhyolite.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] These rhyolite formations can be seen in several city parks and in the yards of a number of private residences.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Indian Rock Park in the northeastern part of Berkeley near the Arlington/Marin Circle features a large example.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is traversed by the Hayward Fault Zone, a major branch of the San Andreas Fault to the west.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] No large earthquake has occurred on the Hayward Fault near Berkeley in historic times (except possibly in 1836), but seismologists warn about the geologic record of large temblors several times in the deeper past.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The current assessment is that a Bay Area earthquake of magnitude 6.7 or greater within the next 30 years is likely, with the Hayward Fault having the highest likelihood among faults in the Bay Area of being the epicenter.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Moreover, like much of the Bay Area, Berkeley has many areas of some risk to soil liquefaction, with the flat areas closer to the shore at low to high susceptibility.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The 1868 Hayward earthquake did occur on the southern segment of the Hayward Fault in the vicinity of today's city of Hayward.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] This quake destroyed the county seat of Alameda County then located in San Leandro, and it subsequently moved to Oakland.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] It was strongly felt in San Francisco, causing major damage.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] It was regarded as the "Great San Francisco earthquake" prior to 1906.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] It produced a furrow in the ground along the fault line in Berkeley, across the grounds of the new State Asylum for the Deaf, Dumb and Blind then under construction, which was noted by one early University of California professor.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Although no significant damage was reported to most of the few Berkeley buildings of the time, the 1868 quake did destroy the vulnerable adobe home of Domingo Peralta in north Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Today, evidence of the Hayward Fault's "creeping" is visible at various locations in Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Cracked roadways, sharp jogs in streams, and springs mark the fault's path.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] However, since it cuts across the base of the hills, the creep is often concealed by or confused with slide activity.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Some of the slide activity itself, however, results from movement on the Hayward Fault.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] A notorious segment of the Hayward Fault runs lengthwise down the middle of Memorial Stadium at the mouth of Strawberry Canyon on the University of California campus.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Photos and measurements show the movement of the fault through the stadium.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has a warm-summer Mediterranean climate (*Csb* in the Köppen climate classification), with warm, dry summers and cool, wet winters.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley's location directly opposite the Golden Gate ensures that typical eastward fog flow blankets the city more often than its neighbors.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The summers are cooler than a typical Mediterranean climate thanks to upwelling ocean currents along the California coast.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] These help produce cool and foggy nights and mornings.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Winter is punctuated with rainstorms of varying ferocity and duration, but also produces stretches of bright sunny days and clear cold nights.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] It does not normally snow, though occasionally the hilltops get a dusting.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Spring and fall are transitional and intermediate, with some rainfall and variable temperature.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Summer typically brings night and morning low clouds or fog, followed by sunny, warm days.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The warmest and driest months are typically June through September, with the highest temperatures occurring in September.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Mid-summer (July–August) is often a bit cooler due to the sea breezes and fog common then.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In a year, there are an average of 2.9 days with highs of 90 °F (32 °C) or higher, and an average of 0.8 days with lows of 32 °F (0 °C) or lower.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The highest recorded temperature was 107 °F (42 °C) on June 15, 2000, and July 16, 1993, and the lowest recorded temperature was 24 °F (−4 °C) on December 22, 1990.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] February is normally the wettest month, averaging 5.21 inches (132 mm) of precipitation.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Average annual precipitation is 25.40 inches (645 mm), falling on an average of 63.7 days each year.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The most rainfall in one month was 14.49 inches (368 mm) in February 1998.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The most rainfall in 24 hours was 6.98 inches (177 mm) on January 4, 1982.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] As in most of California, the heaviest rainfall years are usually associated with warm water El Niño episodes in the Pacific (e.g., 1982–83; 1997–98), which bring in drenching "Pineapple Express" storms.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In contrast, dry years are often associated with cold Pacific La Niña episodes.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Light snow has fallen on rare occasions.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Snow has generally fallen every several years on the higher peaks of the Berkeley Hills.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In the late spring and early fall, strong offshore winds of sinking air typically develop, bringing heat and dryness to the area.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In the spring, this is not usually a problem as vegetation is still moist from winter rains, but extreme dryness prevails by the fall, creating a danger of wildfires.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In September 1923, a major fire swept through the neighborhoods north of the university campus, stopping just short of downtown.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] On October 20, 1991, gusty, hot winds fanned a conflagration along the Berkeley–Oakland border, killing 25 people and injuring 150, as well as destroying 2,449 single-family dwellings and 437 apartment and condominium units.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The 2020 United States census reported that Berkeley had a population of 124,321.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The population density was 11,874 people per square mile of land area (4,584/km2).
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] There were 17,018 (13.7%) of Hispanic or Latino ancestry, of any race.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] According to the 2022 American Community Survey estimate, the median income for a household was $104,716 and the median income for a family was $177,068.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Males had a median income of $102,565 versus $82,772 for females.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The per capita income for the city was $63,310.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] About 4.3% of families and 17.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 6% of those under age 18 and 8.1% of those age 65 or over.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] There were 12,209 people (10.8%) of Hispanic or Latino ancestry, of any race.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] 6.8% of the city's population was of Mexican ancestry.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The Census reported that 99,731 people (88.6% of the population) lived in households, 12,430 (11.0%) lived in non-institutionalized group quarters, and 419 (0.4%) were institutionalized.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] There were 46,029 households, out of which 8,467 (18.4%) had children under the age of 18 living in them, 13,569 (29.5%) were opposite-sex married couples living together, 3,855 (8.4%) had a female householder with no husband present, 1,368 (3.0%) had a male householder with no wife present.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] There were 2,931 (6.4%) unmarried opposite-sex partnerships, and 961 (2.1%) same-sex married couples or partnerships.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] 16,904 households (36.7%) were made up of individuals, and 4,578 (9.9%) had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] There were 18,792 families (40.8% of all households); the average family size was 2.81.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 1.0%; the rental vacancy rate was 4.5%.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] 45,096 people (40.1% of the population) lived in owner-occupied housing units and 54,635 people (48.5%) lived in rental housing units.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] For every 100 females, there were 95.6 males.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 94.2 males.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] According to the 2011 American Community Survey 5-Year estimate, the median income for a household in the city was $60,908, and the median income for a family was $102,976.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Males had a median income of $67,476 versus $57,319 for females.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The per capita income for the city was $38,896.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] About 7.2% of families and 18.3% of the population were below the poverty line, including 13.2% of those under age 18 and 9.2% of those age 65 or over.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has a higher-than-average crime rate, particularly property crime, though the crime rate has fallen significantly since 2000.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is served by Amtrak (Capitol Corridor), AC Transit, BART (Ashby, Downtown Berkeley Station and North Berkeley) and bus shuttles operated by major employers including UC Berkeley and Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The Eastshore Freeway (Interstate 80 and Interstate 580) runs along the bay shoreline.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Each day there is an influx of thousands of cars into the city by commuting UC faculty, staff and students, making parking for more than a few hours an expensive proposition.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has one of the highest rates of bicycle and pedestrian commuting in the nation.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is the safest city of its size in California for pedestrians and cyclists, considering the number of injuries per pedestrian and cyclist, rather than per capita.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has modified its original grid roadway structure through use of diverters and barriers, moving most traffic out of neighborhoods and onto arterial streets (visitors often find this confusing, because the diverters are not shown on all maps).
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley maintains a separate grid of arterial streets for bicycles, called Bicycle Boulevards, with bike lanes and lower amounts of car traffic than the major streets they often parallel.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Attempts to improve the biking infrastructure in Berkeley have been met with controversy.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 2023, the Berkeley city council fired the city's top transportation official for a plan to remove dozens of parking spots on a street to build a protected bike lane.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley hosts car sharing network Zipcar.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Rather than owning (and parking) their own cars, members share a group of cars parked nearby.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Web- and telephone-based reservation systems keep track of hours and charges.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Several "pods" (points of departure where cars are kept) exist throughout the city, in several downtown locations, at the Ashby and North Berkeley BART stations, and at various other locations in Berkeley (and other cities in the region).
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Using alternative transportation is encouraged.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has had recurring problems with parking meter vandalism.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1999, over 2,400 Berkeley meters were jammed, smashed, or sawed apart.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Starting in 2005 and continuing into 2006, Berkeley began to phase out mechanical meters in favor of more centralized electronic meters.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The Berkeley Branch line was extended from Shattuck and University to Vine Street ("Berryman's Station") in 1878.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Starting in 1882, Berkeley trains ran directly to the Oakland Pier.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In the 1880s, Southern Pacific assumed operations of the Berkeley Branch under a lease from its own paper affiliate, the Northern Railway.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] In 1911, Southern Pacific electrified this line and the several others it constructed in Berkeley, creating its East Bay Electric Lines division.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The huge and heavy cars specially built for these lines were called the "Red Trains" or the "Big Red Cars".
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The Shattuck line was extended and connected with two other Berkeley lines (the Ninth Street Line and the California Street line) at Solano and Colusa (the "Colusa Wye").
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] At this time, the Northbrae Tunnel and Rose Street Undercrossing were constructed, both of which still exist.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] (The Rose Street Undercrossing is not accessible to the public, being situated between what is now two backyards.) The fourth Berkeley line was the Ellsworth St. line to the university campus.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The first electric rail service in Berkeley was provided by several small streetcar companies starting in 1891.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Most of these were eventually bought up by the Key System of Francis "Borax" Smith who added lines and improved equipment.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The Key System's streetcars were operated by its East Bay Street Railways division.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Principal lines in Berkeley ran on Euclid, The Arlington, College, Telegraph, Shattuck, San Pablo, University, and Grove (today's Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The last streetcars ran in 1948, replaced by buses.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The first electric commuter interurban-type trains to San Francisco from Berkeley were put in operation by the Key System in 1903, several years before the Southern Pacific electrified its steam commuter lines.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Like the SP, Key trains ran to a pier serviced by the Key's own fleet of ferryboats, which also docked at the Ferry Building in San Francisco.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] After the Bay Bridge was built, the Key trains ran to the Transbay Terminal in San Francisco, sharing tracks on the lower deck of the Bay Bridge with the SP's red trains and the Sacramento Northern Railroad.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] It was at this time that the Key trains acquired their letter designations, which were later preserved by Key's public successor, AC Transit.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Today's F bus is the successor of the F train.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Before the Bridge, these lines were simply the Shattuck Avenue Line, the Claremont Line, the Westbrae Line, and the Sacramento Street Line, respectively.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] After the Southern Pacific abandoned transbay service in 1941, the Key System acquired the rights to use its tracks and catenary on Shattuck north of Dwight Way and through the Northbrae Tunnel to The Alameda for the F-train.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The SP tracks along Monterey Avenue as far as Colusa had been acquired by the Key System in 1933 for the H-train, but were abandoned in 1941.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] The Key System trains stopped running in April 1958.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] On December 15, 1962, the Northbrae Tunnel was opened to auto traffic.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley is the location of a number of nationally prominent businesses, many of which have been pioneers in their areas of operation.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Notable businesses include Chez Panisse, birthplace of California cuisine, Peet's Coffee's original store, the Claremont Resort, punk rock haven 924 Gilman, Saul Zaentz's Fantasy Studios, and Caffe Strada.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Notable former businesses include pioneer bookseller Cody's Books, The Nature Company, The North Face, Clif Bar energy foods, the Berkeley Co-op, and Caffe Mediterraneum.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p01] Berkeley has relatively few chain stores for a city of its size, due to policies and zoning that promote small businesses and impose limits on the size of certain types of stores.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley has a number of distinct neighborhoods.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Surrounding the University of California campus are the most densely populated parts of the city.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] West of the campus is **Downtown Berkeley**, the city's traditional commercial core; home of the civic center, the city's only public high school, the busiest BART station in Berkeley, as well as a major transfer point for AC Transit buses.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] South of the campus is **Southside**, mainly a student ghetto, where much of the university's student housing is located.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The busiest stretch of Telegraph Avenue is in this neighborhood.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] North of the campus is the quieter **Northside** neighborhood, the location of the Graduate Theological Union.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Farther from the university campus, the influence of the university quickly becomes less visible.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Most of Berkeley's neighborhoods are primarily made up of detached houses, often with separate in-law units in the rear, although larger apartment buildings are also common in many neighborhoods.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Commercial activities are concentrated along the major avenues and at important intersections and frequently define the neighborhood within which they reside.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] In the southeastern corner of the city is the **Claremont District**, home to the Claremont Hotel.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Also in the southeast is the **Elmwood District** known for its commercial area on College Avenue.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] West of Elmwood is **South Berkeley**, known for its weekend flea market at the Ashby Station.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] West of (and including) San Pablo Avenue, itself a major commercial and transport corridor, is **West Berkeley**, the historic commercial center of the city.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] This neighborhood and area includes the former unincorporated town of **Ocean View**.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] West Berkeley contains the remnants of Berkeley's industrial area, much of which has been replaced by retail and office uses, as well as residential live/work loft space, paralleling the decline of manufacturing in the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] This area abuts the shoreline of the San Francisco Bay and is home to the Berkeley Marina.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Also nearby is Berkeley's Aquatic Park, featuring an artificial linear lagoon of San Francisco Bay.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] North of downtown is **North Berkeley** which has its main commercial area nicknamed the "Gourmet Ghetto" because of the concentration of well-known restaurants and other food-related businesses.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] West of North Berkeley (roughly west of Sacramento and north of Cedar) is **Westbrae**, a small neighborhood centered on a small commercial area on Gilman Street and through which part of the Ohlone Greenway runs.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Meanwhile, further north of North Berkeley are **Northbrae**, a master-planned subdivision from the early 20th century, and **Thousand Oaks**.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Above these last three neighborhoods, on the western slopes of the Berkeley Hills are the neighborhoods of **Cragmont** and **La Loma Park**, notable for their dramatic views, winding streets, and numerous public stairways and paths.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The city has many parks, and promotes greenery and the environment.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Tilden Regional Park lies east of the city, occupying the upper extent of Wildcat Canyon between the Berkeley Hills and the San Pablo Ridge.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The city is also heavily involved in creek restoration and wetlands restoration, including a planned *daylighting* of Strawberry Creek along Center Street.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley Marina and East Shore State Park flank its shoreline at San Francisco Bay and organizations like the Urban Creeks Council and Friends of the Five Creeks, the former of which is headquartered in Berkeley, support the riparian areas in the town and coastlines as well.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] César Chávez Park, near the Berkeley Marina, was built at the former site of the city dump.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] 165 buildings in Berkeley are designated as local landmarks or local structures of merit.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley is home to the Chilean-American community's La Peña Cultural Center, the largest cultural center for this community in the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The Freight and Salvage is the oldest established full-time folk and traditional music venue west of the Mississippi River.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Additionally, Berkeley is home to the off-Broadway theater Berkeley Repertory Theater, commonly known as "Berkeley Rep".
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley Repertory Theater consists of two stages, a school, and has received a Tony Award for Outstanding Regional Theatre.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The historic Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive (BAMPFA) is operated by UC Berkeley, and was moved to downtown Berkeley in January 2016.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] It offers many exhibitions and screenings of historic films, as well as outreach programs within the community.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] University of California, Berkeley's main campus is in the city limits.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The Graduate Theological Union, a consortium of eight independent theological schools, is located a block north of the University of California Berkeley's main campus.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The Graduate Theological Union has the largest number of students and faculty of any religious studies doctoral program in the United States.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] In addition to more theological schools, Zaytuna College, a newly established Muslim liberal-arts college, has taken 'Holy Hill' as its new home.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The Institute of Buddhist Studies has been located in Berkeley since 1966.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Wright Institute, a psychology graduate school, is located in Berkeley.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley City College is a community college in the Peralta Community College District.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley Unified School District operates public schools.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The first public school in Berkeley was the Ocean View School, now the site of the Berkeley Adult School located at Virginia Street and San Pablo Avenue.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The public schools today are administered by the Berkeley Unified School District.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] In the 1960s, Berkeley was one of the earliest US cities to voluntarily desegregate, utilizing a system of buses, still in use.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The district has eleven elementary schools and one public high school, Berkeley High School (BHS).
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Established in 1880, BHS currently has over 3,000 students.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley High campus was designated a historic district by the National Register of Historic Places on January 7, 2008.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Saint Mary's College High School, a Catholic school, also has its street address in Berkeley, although most of the grounds and buildings are actually in neighboring Albany.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley has 11 public elementary schools and three middle schools.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The East Bay campus of the German International School of Silicon Valley (GISSV) formerly occupied the Hillside Campus, Berkeley, California; it opened there in 2012.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] In December 2016, the GISSV closed the building, due to unmet seismic retrofit needs.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley Public Library serves as the municipal library.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] University of California, Berkeley Libraries operates the University of California Berkeley libraries.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley has a council–manager government.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The mayor is elected at-large for a four-year term and is the ceremonial head of the city and the chair of the city council.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The Berkeley City Council is composed of the mayor and eight council members elected by district who each serve four-year terms.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Districts 2, 3, 5 and 6 hold their elections in years divisible by four while Districts 1, 4, 7 and 8 hold theirs in even-numbered years not divisible by four.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The city council appoints a city manager, who is the chief executive of the city.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Additionally, the city voters directly elect an independent city auditor, school board, and rent stabilization board.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Most city officials, including council members, are elected using instant-runoff voting since November 2010.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] In 2014, the City of Berkeley passed a redistricting measure on the ballot to create the nation's first student supermajority district in District 7, which in 2018 elected Rigel Robinson, a 22-year-old UC Berkeley graduate and the youngest Councilmember in the city's history.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] While much of UC Berkeley's student housing is located in District 7, large dormitories also exist in Districts 6 and 8.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The city's Public Health Division is one of four municipally operated public health agencies in California (the other three being Long Beach, Pasadena, and Vernon).
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Though it is part of the city government, it qualifies for the same state funds as a county public health department.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley is also part of Alameda County, for which the Government of Alameda County is defined and authorized under the California Constitution, California law, and the Charter of the County of Alameda.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The county government provides countywide services, such as elections and voter registration, law enforcement, jails, vital records, property records, tax collection, and social services.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The county's health department does not cover the city.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley has been a Democratic stronghold in presidential elections since 1960, becoming one of the most Democratic cities in the country.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The last Republican presidential candidate to receive at least one-quarter of the vote in Berkeley was Richard Nixon in 1968.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Consistent with Berkeley's reputation as a strongly liberal and/or progressive city, in the 2016 presidential election more votes were won by Green Party presidential candidate Jill Stein than by Republican candidate Donald Trump.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] In the 2020 Presidential election, Joe Biden received 93.8% of the vote while Donald Trump received 4.0% of the vote.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] According to the California Secretary of State, as of October 20, 2025, Berkeley has 75,509 registered voters.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Of those, 55,523 (73.53%) are registered Democrats, 2,317 (3.07%) are registered Republicans, 14,323 (18.97%) have declined to state a political party affiliation, and 3,346 (4.43%) are registered with a third party.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Berkeley became the first city in the United States to pass a sanctuary resolution on November 8, 1971.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The city had a daily newspaper, the *Berkeley Gazette*, which was founded c.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] The *Berkeley Barb* published counter-culture news from 1965 to 1980.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Current media include *The Daily Californian*, the student newspaper of UC Berkeley; the *Berkeley Times*; and local online-only publications *Berkeleyside*, the *Berkeley Daily Planet*, and *The Berkeley Scanner*.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Notable individuals who were born in and/or have lived in Berkeley include Kamala Harris, Steve Wozniak, scientists J.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Robert Oppenheimer and Ernest Lawrence, actors Ben Affleck, and Andy Samberg, Major League Baseball broadcaster Matt Vasgersian, model Rebecca Romijn, Billie Joe Armstrong, lead singer of Green Day, Adam Duritz of Counting Crows, rapper Lil B, authors Ursula K.
[src:cinnaholic/berkeley-california-p02] Le Guin and Michael Chabon, entertainment and real estate mogul Herbie Herbert, and EDM producer KSHMR, and university presidents Blake R.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Catering service is either full-service (with staff setting up, serving, and cleaning up), or drop-off/pickup.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Generally, in the US, catering is served to a group and is based on a common menu.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Restaurants, where guests choose individual dishes from a menu, are not considered caterers; a restaurant may offer catering services, however.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] In British usage the term catering also includes restaurant and pub food service.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] In the UK, the FDA serves as a model for food safety practices in places like restaurants, cafes, takeaways and other food service and catering establishments.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] They provide recommended guidelines on preventing cross-contamination, ensuring proper cleaning, chilling, cooking, management of food and specific guidelines for diary foods to prevent the risk of foodborne illnesses.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] The history of catering reckons back to ancient times.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] The earliest account of major services being catered in the United States was an event for William Howe of Philadelphia in 1778.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] The event served local foods that were a hit with the attendees, who eventually popularized catering as a career.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] The official industry began to be recognized around the 1820s, with the caterers being disproportionately African American.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] The catering business began to form around 1820, centered in Philadelphia.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] The industry began to professionalize under Robert Bogle who is recognized as "the originator of catering." Catering was originally done by servants of wealthy elites.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Butlers and house slaves, who were often black, were in a good position to become caterers.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Essentially, caterers in the 1860s were "public butlers" as they organized and executed the food aspect of a social gathering.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] A public butler was a butler working for several households.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Bogle took on the role of public butler and took advantage of the food service market in the hospitality field.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Caterers like Bogle were involved with events likely to be catered today, such as weddings and funerals.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Bogle also is credited with creating the Guild of Caterers and helping train other black caterers.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] This is important because catering provided not only jobs to black people but also opportunities to connect with elite members of Philadelphia society.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Over time, the clientele of caterers became the middle class, who could not afford lavish gatherings; also, increasing competition from white caterers led to a decline in black catering businesses.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] By the 1840s many restaurant owners began to combine catering services with their shops.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Second-generation caterers grew the industry on the East Coast, becoming more widespread.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Common usage of the word "caterer" came about in the 1880s at which point local directories began to use these term to describe the industry.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] White businessmen took over the industry by the 1900s, with the Black catering population disappearing.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] In the 1930s, the Soviet Union, creating more simple menus, began developing state public catering establishments as part of its collectivization policies.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] A rationing system was implemented during World War II, and people became used to public catering.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] After the Second World War, many businessmen embraced catering as an alternative way of staying in business after the war.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] By the 1960s, the home-made food was overtaken by eating in public catering establishments.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] By the 2000s, personal chef services started gaining popularity, with more women entering the workforce.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] People between 15 and 24 years of age spent as little as 11–17 minutes daily on food preparation and clean-up activities in 2006–2016, according to figures revealed by the American Time Use Survey conducted by the US Bureau of Labor Statistics.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] There are many types of catering, including Event catering, Wedding Catering and Corporate Catering.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] An event caterer serves food at indoor and outdoor events, including corporate and workplace events and parties at home and venues.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] A mobile caterer serves food directly from a vehicle, cart or truck which is designed for the purpose.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Mobile catering is common at outdoor events such as concerts, workplaces, and downtown business districts.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Mobile catering services require less maintenance costs when compared with other catering services.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Mobile caterers may also be known as food trucks in some areas.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Mobile catering is popular throughout New York City, though sometimes can be unprofitable.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Ice cream vans are a familiar example of a catering truck in Canada, the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] A canapé caterer serves canapés at events.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] They have become a popular type of food at events, Christmas parties and weddings.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] A canapé is a type of hors d'oeuvre, a small, prepared, and often decorative food, consisting of a small piece of bread or pastry.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] They should be easier to pick up and not be bigger than one or two bites.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] The bite-sized food is usually served before the starter or main course or alone with drinks at a drinks party.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Canapes are small, elegant appetisers designed to be eaten in one or two bites, often showcasing both taste and aesthetic appeal.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Unlike ordinary hors d’oeuvres, they are curated to make a statement, reflecting the sophistication and style of the event.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] A wedding caterer provides food for a wedding reception and party, traditionally called a wedding breakfast.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] A wedding caterer can be hired independently or can be part of a package designed by the venue.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Catering service providers are often skilled and experienced in preparing and serving high-quality cuisine.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] They offer a diverse and rich selection of food, creating a great experience for their customers.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] There are many different types of wedding caterers, each with their approach to food.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] Merchant ships – especially ferries, cruise liners, and large cargo ships – often carry Catering Officers.
[src:cinnaholic/catering] In fact, the term "catering" was in use in the world of the merchant marine long before it became established as a land-bound business.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] A **chief executive officer** (**CEO**), also known as a **chief executive** or **managing director**, is the top-ranking corporate officer charged with the management of a company or a nonprofit organization.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] CEOs find roles in various organizations, including public and private corporations, nonprofit organizations, and even some government organizations (notably state-owned enterprises).
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The governor and CEO of a corporation or company typically report to the board of directors and are charged with maximizing the value of the business, which may include maximizing the profitability, market share, revenue, or another financial metric.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In the nonprofit and government sector, CEOs typically aim at achieving outcomes related to the organization's mission, usually provided by legislation.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] CEOs are also frequently assigned the role of the main manager of the organization and the highest-ranking officer in the C-suite.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The term "chief executive officer" is attested as early as 1782, when an ordinance of the Congress of the Confederation of the United States of America used the term to refer to governors and other leaders of the executive branches of each of the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In draft additions to the *Oxford English Dictionary* published online in 2011, the *Dictionary* says that the use of "CEO" as an acronym for a chief executive officer originated in Australia, with the first attestation being in 1914.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The first American usage cited is from 1972.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The responsibilities of an organization's CEO are set by the organization's board of directors or other authority, depending on the organization's structure.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] They can be far-reaching or quite limited, and are typically enshrined in a formal delegation of authority regarding business administration.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Typically, responsibilities include being an active decision-maker on business strategy and other key policy issues, as well as leader, manager, and executor roles.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The communicator role can involve speaking to the press and the public, as well as to the organization's management and employees.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The decision-making role entails making high-level decisions regarding policy and strategy.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The CEO is responsible for implementing the goals, targets, and strategic objectives as determined by the board of directors.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] As an executive officer of the company, the CEO reports the status of the business to the board of directors, motivates employees, and drives change within the organization.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] As a manager, the CEO presides over the organization's day-to-day operations.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The CEO is the person who is ultimately accountable for a company's business decisions, including those in operations, marketing, business development, finance, human resources, etc.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The CEO of a political party is often entrusted with fundraising, particularly for election campaigns.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The use of the CEO title may be used by for-profit companies or non-profit or charitable organisations, such as the Wikimedia Foundation.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In some countries, there is a dual board system with two separate boards, one executive board for the day-to-day business and one supervisory board for control purposes (selected by the shareholders).
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In these countries, the CEO presides over the executive board and the chairperson presides over the supervisory board, and these two roles will always be held by different people.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] This ensures a distinction between management by the executive board and governance by the supervisory board.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] This allows for clear lines of authority.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The aim is to prevent a conflict of interest and too much power being concentrated in the hands of one person.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In the United States, the board of directors (elected by the shareholders) is often equivalent to the supervisory board, while the executive board may often be known as the executive committee (the division/subsidiary heads and C-level officers that report directly to the CEO).
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In the United States, and in business, the executive officers are usually the top officers of a corporation, the chief executive officer (CEO) being the best-known type.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The definition varies; for instance, the California Corporate Disclosure Act defines "executive officers" as the five most highly compensated officers not also sitting on the board of directors.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In the case of a sole proprietorship, an executive officer is the sole proprietor.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In the case of a partnership, an executive officer is a managing partner, senior partner, or administrative partner.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In the case of a limited liability company, an executive officer is any member, manager, or officer.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Depending on the organization, a CEO may have several subordinate executives to help run the day-to-day administration of the company, each of whom has specific functional responsibilities referred to as senior executives, executive officers, or corporate officers.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Subordinate executives are given different titles in different organizations, but one common category of subordinate executive, if the CEO is also the president, is the vice president (VP).
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] An organization may have more than one vice president, each tasked with a different area of responsibility (e.g., VP of finance, VP of human resources).
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Examples of subordinate executive officers who typically report to the CEO include the chief operating officer (COO), chief financial officer (CFO), chief strategy officer (CSO), chief marketing officer (CMO), and chief business officer (CBO).
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In the US, the term "chief executive officer" is used primarily in business, whereas the term "executive director" is used primarily in the not-for-profit sector.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] These terms are generally mutually exclusive and refer to distinct legal duties and responsibilities.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The CEO is the highest-ranking executive in a company, making corporate decisions, managing operations, allocating resources, and serving as the main point of communication between the board of directors and the company.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In the UK, chief executive and chief executive officer are used in local government, where their position in law is described as the "head of paid service", and in business and in the charitable sector.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] As of 2013, the use of the term director for senior charity staff is deprecated to avoid confusion with the legal duties and responsibilities associated with being a charity director or trustee, which are normally non-executive (unpaid) roles.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The term **managing director** is often used in lieu of chief executive officer.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Business publicists since the days of Edward Bernays (1891–1995) and his client John D.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Rockefeller (1839–1937) and even more successfully the corporate publicists for Henry Ford, promoted the concept of the "celebrity CEO".
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Business journalists have often adopted this approach, which assumes that the corporate achievements, especially in the arena of manufacturing, are produced by uniquely talented individuals, especially the "heroic CEO".
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In effect, journalists celebrate a CEO who takes distinctive strategic actions.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The model is the celebrity in entertainment, sports, and politics – compare the "great man theory".
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Journalism thereby exaggerates the importance of the CEO and tends to neglect harder-to-describe broader corporate factors.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] There is little attention to the intricately organized technical bureaucracy that actually does the work.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Hubris sets in when the CEO internalizes the celebrity and becomes excessively self-confident in making complex decisions.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] There may be an emphasis on the sort of decisions that attract the celebrity journalists.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Research published in 2009 by Ulrike Malmendier and Geoffrey Tate indicates that "firms with award-winning CEOs subsequently underperform, in terms both of stock and of operating performance".
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] CEOs and senior executives are governed by the board of directors.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The proper selection and evaluation of the CEO and the executive team is critical to the company’s performance.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Yet there is no established standard framework to evaluate and govern the CEO performance.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] One initiative proposes a standardized questionnaire used in annual CEO reviews and senior executive recruitment.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] These questionnaires help guide CEO strategy and assure the shareholders that the company and its executive team are on the right track.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Every CEO and C-level executive must be able to provide specific answers to the preceding questions, readily and clearly.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Additionally, these questions can also be used as a framework for evaluating potential candidates for the succession planning and selection process.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Executive compensation has been a source of criticism following a dramatic rise in pay relative to the average worker's wage.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] For example, the relative pay was 20-to-1 in 1965 in the US, but had risen to 376-to-1 by 2000.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The relative pay differs around the world, and, in some smaller countries, is still around 20-to-1.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Observers differ as to whether the rise is due to competition for talent or due to lack of control by compensation committees.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In recent years, investors have demanded more say over executive pay.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Lack of diversity amongst chief executives has also been a source of criticism.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In 2023 the number rose to 10.4% of for Women CEO's of Fortune 500 companies.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Some countries have passed laws mandating boardroom gender quotas.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In 2023 Rockefeller Foundation awarded a grant to Korn Ferry to research strategies and then action a plan to help more women to become CEO's.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] There are contentious claims that a significant number of CEOs have psychopathic tendencies, often characterized by power-seeking behavior and dominance.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] These individuals can often conceal their ruthlessness and antisocial behavior behind a facade of charm and eloquence.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Traits such as courage and risk-taking, generally considered desirable, are often found alongside these psychopathic tendencies.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Tara Swart, a neuroscientist at MIT Sloan School of Management, has suggested that individuals with psychopathic traits thrive in chaotic environments and are aware that others do not.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] As a result, they may intentionally create chaos in the workplace.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] This perspective is explored in the book *Snakes in Suits*, co-authored by Robert D.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] However, Scott Lilienfeld has argued that the attention given to psychopathy in the workplace by both the media and scholars has far exceeded the available scientific evidence.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Emilia Bunea, writing in *Psychology Today*, has linked psychopathic traits in managers to workplace bullying, employee dissatisfaction, and turnover intentions.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Despite this, Bunea cautions that excessive worry about supposed psychopathic managers could discourage individuals from pursuing careers in corporations and deter employees from addressing issues with difficult bosses.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] There have been several notable controversies involving famous CEOs.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Some of the most prominent controversies were a result of the MeToo Movement including Harvey Weinstein and the Weinstein Company, Steve Wynn and Wynn Resorts Ltd., and Leslie Moonves & CBS.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Elon Musk, the CEO of Tesla, Inc. and SpaceX, has been the subject of several controversies.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] In 2018, Musk tweeted "[a]m considering taking Tesla private at $420.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Funding secured" in the middle of a trading day and a few weeks later, Tesla announced it would go private.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] The SEC investigated Musk shortly after his tweet and charged him with securities fraud.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Musk settled the controversy and stepped down as chair of Tesla's board but remained the company's CEO.
[src:cinnaholic/chief-executive-officer] Musk and Tesla both paid a $20 million penalty to be distributed among harmed investors.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] A **chocolate brownie**, or simply a **brownie**, is a chocolate baked dessert bar.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] Brownies come in a variety of forms and may be either fudgy or cakey, depending on their density.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] Brownies often have a glossy "skin" on their upper crust and may include ingredients such as nuts, frosting, or chocolate chips.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] A variation containing brown sugar and vanilla rather than chocolate in the batter is called a blond brownie or blondie.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] The brownie was developed in the United States at the end of the 19th century and was popularized during the first half of the 20th century.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] Brownies are typically eaten by hand or with utensils, and may be accompanied by a glass of milk, served warm with ice cream (à la mode), topped with whipped cream, or sprinkled with powdered sugar.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] In North America, they are common homemade treats, and they are also popular in restaurants, ice cream parlors, and coffeehouses.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] The same popularity in cafes is seen in Sweden.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] In the Southern United States, brownies prepared from cake mix are a rare homemade dessert eaten on weekdays.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] During the 1880s in the United States, dinner parties themed around the color brown were popular events.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] Following the standard set in lifestyle magazines, hosts served brown dishes—bread, soup, turkey—including sautéed mushrooms, which were then known colloquially as "brownies".
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] One such recipe appeared in the 1896 version of Fannie Farmer's *The Boston Cooking-School Cook Book*, containing molasses and a nut at their center, but no chocolate.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] In 1899, a recipe for an unleavened chocolate cake was published in a Chicago cookbook under the name "Brownie cake".
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] Food writer Stella Parks identifies this as a "proto-brownie", the earliest she could find evidence of.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] Through 1904, recipes for brownies with modern ingredient ratios were published in newspapers in Chicago and the Northeastern United States regions; Parks infers from the broad area and quick succession these recipes appeared that they were drawing on a common source.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] In the 1906 version of her cookbook, Farmer modified her recipe to include chocolate.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] This edition of *The Boston Cooking-School Cook Book* was read widely, and for the first time the entire US was introduced to the brownie, with newspapers and cookbooks printing their own recipes over the following years.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] Recipes for brownies at this time required sugar and butter be creamed, giving these early brownies a cakey rather than fudgy texture.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] Farmer trained Maria Willett Howard who ultimately created Lowney's Brownies for Walter M.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] *The Oxford Encyclopedia of Food and Drink in America* reported that her recipe was often used in New England before 1912.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] By 1907, the brownie was well established in a recognizable form, appearing in *Lowney's Cook Book* by Maria Willet Howard (published by Walter M.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] Lowney Company, Boston) as an adaptation of the Boston Cooking School recipe for a "Bangor Brownie".
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] It added an extra egg and an additional square of chocolate, creating a richer, fudgier dessert.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] The name "Bangor Brownie" appears to have been derived from the town of Bangor, Maine, which an apocryphal story states was the hometown of a housewife who created the original brownie recipe.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] Maine food educator and columnist Mildred Brown Schrumpf was the main proponent of the theory that brownies were invented in Bangor.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] One legend about the creation of brownies is that of Bertha Palmer, a prominent Chicago socialite whose husband owned the Palmer House Hotel.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] In 1893, Palmer asked a pastry chef for a dessert suitable for ladies attending the Chicago World's Columbian Exposition.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] She requested a dessert that would be smaller than a piece of cake, and easily eaten from boxed lunches.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] The result was the Palmer House Brownie, made of chocolate with walnuts and an apricot glaze.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] The Palmer House Hotel still serves this dessert to patrons made from the same recipe.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] The name was given to the dessert some time after 1893, but was not used by cookbooks or journals at the time.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] During the 1960s, brownies were introduced to TV dinners.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] Early recipes, such as Lowney's Brownies, included chocolate, butter, eggs, salt, sugar, vanilla, flour, and chopped nuts, while modern recipes also include brown sugar.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] The 1976 edition of Lizzie Black Kander's *The Settlement Cook Book* also includes cocoa powder as a replacement for chocolate, baking powder, and walnuts.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] The book states that butter and chocolate should be melted together, while beaten eggs and sugar should be added to a separate mixture.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] The two should then be combined and beaten again, after which the remaining ingredients should be added.
[src:cinnaholic/chocolate-brownie] Corriher wrote that brownies can sometimes also include dried cherries and coffee beans.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] All of Cinnaholic's products are 100 percent vegan, dairy and lactose-free, egg-free and cholesterol-free.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] In addition to cinnamon rolls, Cinnaholic serves scratch-made brownies, raw chocolate chip cookie dough, baked chocolate chip cookies, cinnamon roll cakes and bite-sized cinnamon rolls called 'Baby Buns'.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] The company's co-founders, Shannon and Florian Radke, appeared on the television show *Shark Tank* in 2014, which ended with the pair initially accepting an offer from Robert Herjavec and then later declining the offer.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] Cinnaholic is headquartered in Atlanta, Georgia.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] Shannon and Florian Radke opened the first Cinnaholic bakery on Oxford Street in Berkeley, California, in July 2010.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] The husband and wife team appeared on the television show *Shark Tank* in 2014, which ended in an investment offer.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] The company adopted a franchise business model in 2015.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] Cinnaholic Franchising, LLC moved its headquarters from Berkeley, California, to Atlanta, Georgia.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] Cinnaholic's first franchise-operated bakeshop opened in Southlake, Texas, near Dallas in October 2015.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] The company opened its first international bakery in Edmonton, Alberta, Canada, in May 2018.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] Cinnaholic was named to *Entrepreneur* magazine's "Top New Franchisees of 2018" list.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] Co-founder, Shannon Radke, appeared on the cover of the September 2018 issue of *Franchise Times* Magazine.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnaholic] The couple were also featured in *Diablo Magazine*'s "40 under 40" issue in January 2014.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] A **cinnamon roll** (also known as **cinnamon bun**, **cinnamon swirl**, **cinnamon scroll**, **cinnamon Danish** and **cinnamon snail**) is a sweet roll commonly served in Northern Europe and North America.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] Alternative recipes use puff pastry instead of yeasted dough, but are constructed using a similar method.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] A cinnamon roll consists of a rolled sheet of yeast-leavened sweet bread dough or Viennoiserie, onto which a cinnamon and sugar mixture (with some variations including brown sugar, raisins or other ingredients) is sprinkled over a thin coat of butter.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] The dough is then rolled, cut into individual portions and normally baked, however a deep fried version is called cinnamon roll or cinnamon bun doughnut.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] Arab spice traders introduced the Sri Lankan cinnamon spice to Europe.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] The origin of cinnamon rolls is unknown, but might be in Byzantium.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] The oldest recorded recipes for cinnamon rolls are from Germany in the 16th century.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] Cinnamon rolls spread from Germany to Scandinavia, introduced to Norway from Hanseatic traders through the port city of Bergen where it would become known as the *skillingsbolle* (lit.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] ''shilling bun''), with the modern Swedish *kanelbulle* (lit.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] ''cinnamon bun'') being created after the First World War.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] They spread to the United States with German immigrants.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] The size of a cinnamon roll varies from place to place, but many vendors supply a smaller size about 5 centimeters (2.0 in) in diameter and a larger size about 10 cm (3.9 in) to a side.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] One of the larger varieties can be found in Finland, called *korvapuusti* (lit.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] "pulling someone's ear for disciplining"), where it can be up to 20 cm (7.9 in) in diameter and weigh up to 200 g (7.1 oz).
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] Haga, a district in Gothenburg, Sweden, has very large cinnamon rolls.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] These cinnamon rolls are called *hagabullar* or *Queen of the Kitchen*.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] *Hagabullar* are usually 30 centimeters (12 in) or more in diameter and are, despite their size, not considered a communal roll.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] In Iceland it is known as *kanilsnúður*, and in Estonia it is known as *kaneelirull*.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] In Austria and Germany, it is called *Zimtschnecke*.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] In Slovakia and the Czech Republic, it is called *škoricové slimáky*/*skořicoví šneci* (meaning 'cinnamon snails').
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] Since 1999, October 4 has been promoted as Cinnamon Roll Day (*Kanelbullens dag*), a national theme day, acknowledged by a significant portion of the Swedish population.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] Swedish kanelbulle dough typically also contains cardamom (powder or buds), giving it a distinctive flavour.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] The Swedish *Butterkaka* and Finnish *bostonkakku* ("Boston cake") is a cake made by baking cinnamon rolls in a round cake pan instead of baking them separately, so that they stick together to form a large, round cake.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] In Austria and Germany, they are widely available at supermarkets and bakeries.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] A German variety, which is similar to the Scandinavian style, originating in Hamburg and its surroundings is the *Franzbrötchen*, a cinnamon-filled baked good inspired by the French croissant, which does not contain cinnamon.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] In the United Kingdom, cinnamon bun, cinnamon roll and cinnamon swirl names are all used, and generally available in most supermarkets and bakeries.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] American cinnamon rolls are frequently large, baked in a pan and topped with cream cheese icing (usually confectioners' sugar-based) and are sometimes fried, finished with glaze, and served as a variation of a raised donut.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] In some areas, particularly in the American Midwest, cinnamon rolls are commonly served with chili, a combination that originated with school lunches in those areas.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] In Canada, they are known as cinnamon rolls or cinnamon buns.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] They are also iced with cream cheese icing or a glaze.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] In Asian cultures, cinnamon rolls may be made using a yeast bread technique called tangzhong.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] The technique is associated with Japanese milk bread since it gives it a soft, feathery texture.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] By heating flour at exactly 65°C or 149°F, the starches within the flour will pre-gelatinize, causing it to thicken more than average.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] Tangzhong allows the starches to retain moisture for longer periods of time, resulting in a longer shelf life.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] In Sweden and Finland, cinnamon rolls are traditionally enjoyed during a get-together, including the consumption of coffee and or baked goods.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] In Sweden, the get-together is known as a *fika*, typically held in the afternoon, by coworkers during a break, by friends or by family.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] National Cinnamon Roll Day (*Kanelbullens dag*) is observed on October 4 in Sweden and Finland.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] In Denmark, cinnamon buns are especially popular on Wednesdays, where an extra large variant called the Wednesday snail is sold.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] This tradition was specially invented during the 1990s where the national football team usually played their games on Wednesdays.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] Along with Topfengolatsche, Buttercroissant and Faschingskrapfen, cinnamon rolls are a typical baked good to have with afternoon coffee, known as "Kaffe und Kuchen" in Austria and Germany.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] In North America, cinnamon rolls are commonly eaten for breakfast or dessert.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] When eaten for breakfast in the U.S., they may be served with cream cheese frosting.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] Cinnamon buns are particularly popular during the Christmas season in Slovakia and the Czech Republic.
[src:cinnaholic/cinnamon-roll] They form part of the traditional Christmas baking repertoire in many households, alongside other festive treats like vanilla crescents (vanilkové rožteky) and linzer cookies.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee production begins when the seeds from coffee cherries, the *Coffea* plant's fruits, are separated to produce unroasted green coffee beans.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The "beans" are roasted and then ground into fine particles.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee is brewed from the ground roasted beans, which are typically steeped in hot water before being filtered out.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] It is usually served hot, although chilled or iced coffee is common.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee can be prepared and presented in a variety of ways, e.g., espresso, French press, caffè latte, or already-brewed canned coffee.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Sugar, sugar substitutes, milk, and cream are often added to mask the bitter taste or enhance the flavor.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Though coffee has become a global commodity, it has a history tied to food traditions around the Red Sea.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The earliest reports of coffee drinking pertain to the plant's use among the Sufis of Yemen in southern Arabia in the middle of the 15th century.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Up to the end of the 17th century, most of the world's coffee was imported from Yemen.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] As it gained in popularity, coffee started to be cultivated in Java in the 17th century and the Americas from the 18th century.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The two most commonly grown coffee bean types are *C. arabica* and *C. robusta*.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee plants are cultivated in over 70 countries, primarily in the equatorial regions of the Americas, Southeast Asia, the Indian subcontinent, and Africa.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Green, unroasted coffee is traded as an agricultural commodity.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The global coffee industry was worth $495.50 billion in 2023.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] In 2023, Brazil was the leading grower of coffee beans, producing 31% of the world's total, followed by Vietnam.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] While coffee sales reach billions of dollars annually worldwide, coffee farmers disproportionately live in poverty.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Critics of the coffee industry have pointed to its negative impact on the environment, including clearing of land for coffee growing and water use.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The word *coffee* entered the English language in 1582 via the Dutch *koffie*, borrowed from the Ottoman Turkish *kahve* (قهوه), borrowed from the Arabic *qahwah* (قَهْوَة).
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Medieval Arabic lexicons traditionally held that the etymology of *qahwah* meant 'wine', given its distinctly dark color, and was derived from the verb *qahiya* (قَهِيَ), 'to have no appetite'.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The word *qahwah* most likely meant 'the dark one', referring to the brew or the bean.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The terms *coffee pot* and *coffee break* originated in 1705 and 1952, respectively.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] There are multiple anecdotal origin stories which lack evidence.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Hattox records traditions in which the Islamic prophet Muhammad is said to have been introduced to a stimulating beverage by the Angel Gabriel, who recommended it for its restorative qualities.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] In another commonly repeated legend, Kaldi, a 9th-century Ethiopian or Arab goatherd, first observed the coffee plant after seeing his flock energized by chewing on the plant.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The herder is unnamed in the earliest account and the name Kaldi appears to be a later invention the twentieth century.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Another legend attributes the discovery of coffee to a Sheikh Omar.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Starving after being exiled from Mokha, Omar found berries.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] After attempting to chew and roast them, Omar boiled them, which yielded a liquid that revitalized and sustained him.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] According to later accounts, bunchum was made from a root rather than from coffee beans.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] There is no confirmed evidence, either historical or archaeological, of coffee as a drink being consumed before the 15th century.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The drink appears to be a relatively recent development.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] By the late 15th century, coffee drinking was well established among Sufi communities in Yemen.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee appears to have been likely collected from wild, with some indications that its use expanded from the 14th century among certain Islamized groups in southeastern Ethiopia, though direct evidence for early consumption remains scarce.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The use of coffee is believed to have spread across the Red Sea to the Rasulid sultanate of Yemen, who maintained cultural and commercial ties with the Adal Sultanate.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Its consumption first appears in Yemen, particularly in regions such as Aden, Mocha and Zabid during the 15th century.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The 16th-century scholar Ibn Hajar al-Haytami writes about the plant's development from a tree in the Zeila region.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] In 1542, a Portuguese crew met with a ship from Zeila transporting clarified butter and coffee to Al-Shihr in Yemen.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Other sources of coffee drinking or knowledge of the coffee tree appear in the middle of the 15th century in the accounts of Ahmed al-Ghaffar in Yemen, where coffee seeds were first roasted and brewed in a similar way to how it is prepared now.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee was used by Sufi circles to stay awake for their religious rituals.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Accounts differ on the origin of the coffee plant before its appearance in Yemen.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee may have been introduced to Yemen from Ethiopia via the Red Sea trade.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] One account credits Muhammad Ibn Sa'd al-Dhabḥani for bringing coffee to Aden from the Somali coast, other early accounts say Ali ben Omar of the Shadhili Sufi order was the first to introduce coffee to Arabia.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] By the 16th century, coffee had reached the rest of the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Within the Ottoman Empire, the first coffeehouse opened in 1555 in Tahtakale, Istanbul.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Since Tahtakale is to the West of the Bosporus, this would likely have been the first coffee house in Europe.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Thriving trade brought many goods, including coffee, from the Ottoman Empire to Venice.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee became more widely accepted in Europe after Pope Clement VIII declared it a Christian beverage in 1600, despite appeals to ban the "Muslim drink".
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee had spread to Italy by 1600 and then to the rest of Europe, Indonesia, and the Americas.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The first European coffeehouse outside of the Ottoman Empire opened in Venice in 1647.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] developed methods for large scale commercial manufacture of instant coffee.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The Dutch East India Company was the first to import coffee on a large scale.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The Dutch later grew the crop in Java and Ceylon.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The first exports of Indonesian coffee from Java to the Netherlands occurred in 1711.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Through the efforts of the British East India Company, coffee became popular in England.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] In a diary entry of May 1637, John Evelyn records tasting the drink at Oxford, where it had been brought by a student of Balliol College from Crete named Nathaniel Conopios of Crete.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Oxford's Queen's Lane Coffee House, established in 1654, is still in existence today.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee was introduced in France in 1657 and in Austria and Poland after the 1683 Battle of Vienna, when coffee was captured from supplies of the defeated Turks.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] When coffee reached North America during the Colonial period, it was initially not as successful as in Europe, as alcoholic beverages remained more popular.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] During the 18th century, coffee consumption declined in Britain, giving way to tea drinking.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Tea was simpler to make and had become cheaper with the British conquest of India and the tea industry there.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] During the Age of Sail, seamen aboard ships of the British Royal Navy made substitute coffee by dissolving burnt bread in hot water.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] According to Captain Haines, who was the colonial administrator of Aden (1839–1854), Mokha historically imported up to two-thirds of its coffee from Berbera-based merchants before the coffee trade of Mokha was captured by British-controlled Aden in the 19th century.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] After that, much of the Ethiopian coffee was exported to Aden via Berbera.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Frenchman Gabriel de Clieu took a coffee plant to the French territory of Martinique in the Caribbean in the 1720s, from which much of the world's cultivated arabica coffee is descended.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee thrived in the climate and was conveyed across the Americas.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee was cultivated in Saint-Domingue, now Haiti, from 1734, and by 1788 it supplied half the world's coffee.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The conditions that the enslaved people worked in on coffee plantations were a factor in the Haitian Revolution, and the coffee industry never fully recovered there.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] In the late 16th century, Yemen developed a booming coffee economy.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Farmers grew coffee on mountain terraces above the Tihamah plain, and trade routes linked its ports to Jeddah and Cairo.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] By the 17th century, coffee had surpassed the global spice trade.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Up to the end of the 17th century, Yemen was the world's main producer for coffee, and Mocha was the world's largest shipping port for coffee.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee was introduced to Brazil in 1727, but its cultivation did not gather momentum until independence in 1822.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] After this time, massive tracts of rainforest were cleared for coffee plantations, first around Rio de Janeiro and later São Paulo.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Brazil went from having essentially no coffee exports in 1800 to being a significant regional producer in 1830, to being the largest producer in the world by 1852.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Between 1910 and 1920, Brazil exported around 70% of the world's coffee; Colombia, Guatemala, and Venezuela exported 15%; and Old World production accounted for less than 5% of world exports.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Many countries in Central America took up cultivation in the latter half of the 19th century, and almost all were involved in the large-scale displacement and exploitation of indigenous people.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Harsh conditions led to many uprisings, coups, and bloody suppression of peasants.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The notable exception was Costa Rica, where a lack of ready labor prevented the formation of large farms.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Smaller farms and more egalitarian conditions ameliorated unrest over the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Rapid growth in coffee production in South America during the second half of the 19th century was matched by an increase in consumption in developed countries.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Nowhere was this growth been as pronounced as in the United States, where a high rate of population growth was compounded by doubling of per capita consumption between 1860 and 1920.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Though the United States was not the heaviest coffee-drinking nation at the time, Belgium, the Netherlands and Nordic countries all had comparable or higher levels of per capita consumption, due to its sheer size, the US was already the largest consumer of coffee in the world by 1860.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] By 1920, around half of all coffee produced worldwide was consumed in the US.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee has become a vital cash crop for many developing countries.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Over 100 million people in developing countries have become dependent on coffee as their primary source of income.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] It has become the primary export and economic backbone for African countries like Uganda, Burundi, Rwanda, and Ethiopia, as well as many Central American countries.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Several species of shrub of the genus *Coffea* produce the berries from which coffee is extracted.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The two main species commercially cultivated are *C. canephora* (predominantly a form known as 'robusta') and *C. arabica*.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] *C. arabica*, the most highly regarded species, is native to the southwestern highlands of Ethiopia, the Boma Plateau in southeastern Sudan, and Mount Marsabit in northern Kenya.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] *C. canephora* is native to western and central Subsaharan Africa, from Guinea to Uganda and southern Sudan.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Less popular species are *C. liberica*, *C. stenophylla*, *C. mauritiana*, and *C. racemosa*.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] All coffee plants are classified in the family Rubiaceae.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] They are evergreen shrubs or trees that may grow 5 m (15 ft) tall when unpruned.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The leaves are dark green and glossy, usually 10–15 cm (4–6 in) long and 6 cm (2.4 in) wide, simple, entire, and opposite.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Petioles of opposite leaves fuse at the base to form interpetiolar stipules, characteristic of Rubiaceae.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The flowers are axillary, and clusters of fragrant white flowers bloom simultaneously.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Gynoecium consists of an inferior ovary, also characteristic of Rubiaceae.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The flowers are followed by oval berries of about 1.5 cm (0.6 in).
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] When immature, they are green, and they ripen to yellow, then crimson, before turning black on drying.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Each berry usually contains two seeds, but 5–10% of the berries have only one; these are called peaberries.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Arabica berries ripen in six to eight months, while robusta takes nine to eleven months.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The traditional method of planting coffee is to place 20 seeds in each hole at the beginning of the rainy season.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] This method loses about 50% of the seeds' potential, as about half fail to sprout.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] A more effective process of growing coffee, used in Brazil, is to raise seedlings in nurseries that are then planted outside after six to twelve months.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee is often intercropped with food crops, such as corn, beans, or rice during the first few years of cultivation as farmers become familiar with its requirements.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Coffee plants grow within a defined area between the tropics of Cancer and Capricorn, termed the bean belt or coffee belt.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] In 2020, the world production of green coffee beans was 175,647,000 60 kg bags, led by Brazil with 39% of the total, followed by Vietnam, Colombia, and Indonesia.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Brazil is the largest coffee exporting nation, accounting for 15% of all world exports in 2019.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] As of 2021, no synthetic coffee products are publicly available but multiple bioeconomy companies have reportedly produced first batches that are highly similar on the molecular level and are close to commercialization.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Of the two main species grown, arabica coffee (from *C. arabica*) is generally more highly regarded than robusta coffee (from *C. canephora*).
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Robusta coffee tends to be bitter and has less flavor but a better body than arabica.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] For these reasons, about three-quarters of the coffee cultivated worldwide is *C. arabica*.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Robusta strains contain about 40–50% more caffeine than arabica.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Consequently, this species is used as an inexpensive substitute for arabica in many commercial coffee blends.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Good quality robusta beans are used in traditional Italian espresso blends to provide a full-bodied taste and a better foam head (known as *crema*).
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] Robusta is less susceptible to disease than arabica and can be cultivated in lower altitudes and warmer climates where arabica does not thrive.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The robusta strain was first collected in 1890 from the Lomani River, a tributary of the Congo River, and was conveyed from the Congo Free State (now the Democratic Republic of the Congo) to Brussels to Java around 1900.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] From Java, further breeding resulted in the establishment of robusta plantations in many countries.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] In particular, the spread of the devastating coffee leaf rust, caused by the fungal pathogen *Hemileia vastatrix*, hastened the uptake of the resistant robusta.
[src:cinnaholic/coffee-p01] The pathogen results in light, rust-colored spots on the undersides of coffee plant leaves.
